column84: COMMUNITY SERVICES: WORKS WITH COMMUNITY MEMBERS FROM EAST BOSTON TO IMPROVE THE ENVIRONMENT, ENHANCE THE QUALITY OF LIFE AND DEVELOP LEADERSHIP SKILLS OF RESIDENTS OF EAST BOSTON AND BEYOND. FINANCIAL LITERACY, CREDIT AND BUDGETING EDUCATION: PROVIDES LOW-AND MODERATE INCOME COMMUNITY MEMBERS UP TO EIGHT HOURS OF FREE COURSEWORK TEACHING HOW TO ESTABLISH AND MAINTAIN A RECORD OF GOOD CREDIT, HOW TO UNDERSTAND CREDIT SCORING AND HOW TO SET AND REACH FINANCIAL GOALS. column40: OUR MISSION IS TO GATHER, PRESERVE AND DISSEMINATE HISTORY FOR THE ENJOYMENT AND EDUCATION OF YOUNG AND OLD, RESIDENTS AND TRAVELERS ALIKE
column80: TO GATHER, PRESERVE AND DISSEMINATE HISTORY FOR THE ENJOYMENT AND EDUCATION OF YOUNG AND OLD, RESIDENTS AND TRAVELERS ALIKE
column84: THE ACHS GATHERED THE STORIES AND ARTIFACTS OF ANOKA COUNTY THROUGH SYSTEMATIC INQUIRY WITH THE PUBLIC REGARDING THEIR HOLDINGS AND THE IDENTIFIED VOIDS IN THE COLLECTION. WEEKLY WE ASSESSED BOTH 3-D AND 2-D MATERIALS TO DETERMINE THEIR PROVENANCE, RELEVANCE, AND ABILITY TO ENCAPSULATE THE IDENTITY OF THE COMMUNITY. THE ACHS PRESERVED THE STORIES OF ANOKA COUNTY BY USING OUR NEWLY REDESIGNED POLICY, FORMS, AND PROCESS. STAFF HAS MADE SIGNIFICANT ADVANCES IN THE EFFICIENT USE OF STORAGE SPACE BY REDESIGNING THE ROLLED OBJECTS RACK, FRAMED OBJECTS RACK, AND SHIFTING ARTIFACTS TO MORE APPROPRIATELY SIZED BOXES. THE ACHS DISSEMINATED HISTORY TO THE COMMUNITY THROUGH A NUMBER OF EDUCATIONAL EFFORTS. OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH THE LIBRARY CONTINUES, ALLOWING STAFF TO PRESENT HOUR-LONG TOPICAL FEATURES TO A NEW AND WIDER AUDIENCE AT A VARIETY OF LOCATIONS THROUGHOUT THE COUNTY. WE CONTINUE TO PARTNER WITH THE SCHOOLS TO PROVIDE IN-CLASSROOM PRESENTATIONS. THIS RELATIONSHIP HAS GROWN TO INCLUDE A PILOT PROJECT OF EDUCATION BOXES FULL OF SUPPLEMENTAL MATERIAL THAT FOLLOWS THE NORTHERN LIGHTS CURRICULUM DEVELOPED BY THE MINNESOTA HISTORICAL SOCIETY. FOUR TEACHERS COMMITTED TO BRINGING 70 STUDENTS TO THE MUSEUM AFTER SCHOOL FOR A YOUNG HISTORIANS CLUB. ACHS REACHED A GOAL OF IMPROVED OUTREACH BY PARTICIPATING IN THE TEDXFRIDLEY EVENT AS A SPEAKER, APPEARING AT COUNCIL AND CIVIC CLUB MEETINGS, AS WELL AS PARTICIPATING IN A NEW CHAMBER OF NONPROFITS BEGUN IN ANOKA COUNTY THIS YEAR.

column84: TEXAS VETERANS TRANSITION PROGRAM: SERVED 352 VETERANS, 50 FAMILY MEMBERS AND 6 SURVIVORS; WITH 70% SEEKING CAREER SERVICES AND 30% OTHER CONCERNS SUCH AS PERSONAL, TRAUMA, AND FAMILY COUNSELING AND LEGAL/FINANCIAL ADVISEMENT. THE MAJORITY OF THE 70% SOUGHT AND WERE PROVIDED OTHER SERVICES INCLUDING 51% INDIVIDUAL CAREER/TRAINING SESSIONS, 25% PERSONAL COUNSELING, 14% LEGAL/FINANCIAL AND 10% FAMILY. OF THOSE SERVED, 28% OF THE VETERANS WERE FEMALE AND 72% MALE. OUTREACH INCLUDED HIRING EVENTS, BENEFIT FAIRS, DEPLOYMENT READINESS, GUARD AND RESERVE FAMILY DAYS, AND COLLABORATIVE MEETINGS AMONG SERVICE PROVIDERS. UTLIZING ONLINE MEDIA, PUBLISHED WEEKLY "VETERANS NEWSLETTER AND "VETERAN-EMPLOYER CONNECTION" WITH JOB OPENINGS SENT BY VETERAN-FRIENDLY COMPANIES. ALSO PROVIDED QUARTERLY NEWSLETTER TO INSTITUTE PARTNERS AND SUPPORTERS. MAINTAINED ONLINE DATABASE OF CURRENT CLIENT RESUMES. CONTINUED TO DEVELOP TEXAS ALLIANCE OF MILITARY WOMEN OFFERING MENTORING TO MILITARY WOMEN NEWLY IN TRANSITION. SET GROUNDWORK TO ESTABLISH OUTREACH PROGRAMS FOR AREA WOMEN VETERANS. column96: TOUCH A LIFE WORKS WITH STREET CHILDREN IN VIETNAM. column40: TECHNOSERVE HELPS ENTERPRISING MEN AND WOMEN IN POOR AREAS OF THE DEVELOPING WORLD.
column80: WE WORK WITH ENTERPRISING PEOPLE IN THE DEVELOPING WORLD TO BUILD COMPETITIVE FARMS, BUSINESSES AND INDUSTRIES.
column84: TECHNOSERVE IS A LEADER IN HARNESSING THE POWER OF THE PRIVATE SECTOR TO HELP PEOPLE LIFT THEMSELVES OUT OF POVERTY. A NONPROFIT ORGANIZATION OPERATING IN 29 COUNTRIES, WE WORK WITH ENTERPRISING MEN AND WOMEN IN THE DEVELOPING WORLD TO BUILD COMPETITIVE FARMS, BUSINESSES AND INDUSTRIES. IN 2015, TECHNOSERVE'S WORK DIRECTLY BENEFITTED 319,000 FARMERS, BUSINESSES AND EMPLOYEES, IMPROVING THE LIVES OF AN ESTIMATED 1.6 MILLION HOUSEHOLD MEMBERS. WE HELPED THESE BENEFICIARIES GENERATE $75.3 MILLION IN ADDITIONAL REVENUE AND WAGES. AS AN INDICATION OF LONG-TERM GROWTH WE HELPED CATALYZE $36.5 MILLION IN PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT IN FARMS AND BUSINESSES. BREAKING THIS IMPACT DOWN INTO REGIONS, LATIN AMERICA AND THE CARIBBEAN HAD THE LARGEST NUMBERS, SEEING $29.6 MILLION IN ADDITIONAL REVENUE AND WAGES, BENEFITTING 48,000 FARMERS, BUSINESS AND EMPLOYEES AND GENERATING $36.5 MILLION IN PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT. EAST AFRICA ALSO HAD STRONG NUMBERS WITH $25.7 MILLION IN ADDED REVENUE AND WAGE, 180,000 DIRECT BENEFICIARIES AND $11.1 MILLION IN PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT. WEST AND SOUTHERN AFRICA HAD A COMBINED IMPACT OF $19.3 MILLION IN REVENUE AND WAGES, 87,000 DIRECT BENEFICIARIES AND $8.4 MILLION IN PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT. OUR EFFORTS IN THE COUNTRY OF INDIA GENERATED $700,000 IN ADDITIONAL REVENUE AND WAGES, BEFITTED 4,000 BENEFICIARIES AND CATALYZED $300,000 IN PRIVATE SECTOR INVESTMENT.IN MEXICO, TECHNOSERVE HAS SUPPORTED 4,000 AGRICULTURE AND DAIRY SMALLHOLDERS SINCE 2011. TECHNOSERVE HAS PROVIDED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND BUSINESS SUPPORT TO HELP SMALL FARMERS INCREASE PRODUCTIVITY AND QUALITY. MORE THAN 8 FARMER ORGANIZATIONS HAVE BEEN ABLE TO SELL THEIR PRODUCT DIRECTLY WITHOUT INTERMEDIARIES TO MULTINATIONAL CORPORATIONS. AGRICULTURE FARMERS HAVE OBSERVED PRICE INCREMENTALS FROM 10 TO 100 PERCENT, DEPENDING ON THE CROP. FARMERS HAVE SOLD TOMATO, ZUCCHINI, GRAPEFRUIT, WATERMELON, MELON, LEMON, MANGO, BROCCOLI AND OTHER VEGETABLES FULFILLING QUALITY SPECIFICATIONS. IN DAIRY, MORE THAN 300 FARMERS HAVE IMPROVED THEIR INFRASTRUCTURE AND TECHNICAL SKILLS INCREASING LITERS PER COW AND COWS PER FARMER. THE FIRST COHORT OF DAIRY FARMERS HAS ALREADY TRIPLED THEIR NET INCOMES.IN CENTRAL AMERICA AND THE CARIBBEAN, TECHNOSERVE CONTINUES TO CATALYZE ENTREPRENEURSHIP THROUGH ITS IMPULSA TU EMPRESA PROGRAM. IN 2015, TECHNOSERVE SUPPORTED MORE THAN 550 ENTREPRENEURS ACROSS NICARAGUA, HONDURAS, GUATEMALA, AND EL SALVADOR, THE LARGEST NUMBER IN A SINGLE YEAR TO DATE. THE PROGRAM PROVIDES BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT SUPPORT TO SMALL AND GROWING BUSINESS IN THE REGION FOR THE ENTERPRISES IT SUPPORTS. TECHNOSERVE HAS ALSO BEEN A LEADER IN DEVELOPING THE COFFEE SECTOR IN THE REGION WITH COFFEE PROJECTS IN GUATEMALA AND HONDURAS. IN HONDURAS THE SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURAL IMPROVEMENT PROJECT BENEFITTED MORE THAN 26,500 SMALL SCALE COFFEE AND BEAN PRODUCERS IN 2015. THE COFFEE FARMERS HAVE SEEN THEIR COFFEE REVENUES INCREASE BY 60 PERCENT.IN SOUTH AMERICA, THE ORGANIZATION RECEIVED AN EXTENSION FROM ITS PARTNER ON ITS SUCCESSFUL ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT ALLIANCE FOR SAN MARTIN PROGRAM. THE PROGRAM HAS BEEN WORKING TO TRANSITION THE ECONOMY FROM COCA CULTIVATION TO COFFEE AND COCOA PRODUCTION. OVER THE FIVE YEARS OF THE PROGRAM, IT HAS ASSISTED MORE THAN 21,000 COCOA FARMERS TO INCREASE YIELDS BY 38 PERCENT AND THEY HAVE SOLD OVER $10.5 MILLION BEANS DIRECTLY TO EXPORTERS.IN SUB-SAHARAN AFRICA, THE PROGRAM CONTINUES TO HAVE A LARGE FOOTPRINT WITH A NUMBER OF SUCCESSES IN EAST AFRICA, WEST AFRICA AND SOUTHERN AFRICA. IN EAST AFRICA, THE STRENGTHENING RURAL YOUTH THROUGH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM CONTINUES TO BE QUITE SUCCESSFUL. WITH THE COMPLETION OF THE FIRST PHASE OF THE PROJECT, THE SECOND PHASE OF THE PROGRAM ANNOUNCED IN 2015 LOOKS TO SCALE THE PROGRAM TO NEW GEOGRAPHIES AND STRENGTHEN AFTERCARE FOR THE YOUNG ENTREPRENEURS. NEARLY 15,500 YOUTH HAVE SUCCESSFULLY GRADUATED FROM THE PROGRAM AND INCOMES HAVE INCREASED BY 133 PERCENT.IN SOUTHERN AFRICA, ENTREPRENEURSHIP SUPPORT FOR WOMEN AND YOUTH IS A HIGHLIGHT. THE ACCELERATING WOMEN AND YOUTH ENTERPRISES IN SOUTH AFRICAN METROS PROGRAM COMPLETED ITS SECOND CYCLE IN 2015. ALL BUSINESSES THAT COMPLETED THE PROGRAM REPORTED AN INCREASE IN THEIR REVENUES, FOR A COMBINED TOTAL OF NEARLY $125,000, AFTER THE SUPPORT FROM THE PROGRAM.IN WEST AFRICA, THE CASHEW LIVELIHOOD PROGRAM IS HELPING TO RAISE THE INCOMES OF 6,000 NIGERIAN CASHEW FARMERS THROUGH TRAINING ON GOOD AGRONOMIC PRACTICES, FARMING AS A BUSINESS AND IMPROVED HARVEST METHODS. THE PROGRAM'S GREAT SUCCESS HAS BEEN ITS ABILITY TO ENGAGE FEMALE CASHEW FARMERS, WHO MAKE UP 47 PERCENT OF THE FARMERS ENROLLED IN THE TRAINING PROGRAM DESPITE ONLY CONSTITUTING LESS THAN 15 PERCENT OF NIGERIA'S CASHEW FARMERS.IN INDIA, TECHNOSERVE CONTINUES TO SUPPORT AGRICULTURE AND ENTREPRENEURSHIP. IN 2015, TECHNOSERVE PILOTED A PROGRAM TO SUPPORT FEMALE FARMERS THROUGH THE FORMATION OF PRODUCER ORGANIZATIONS. THE PROGRAM IS HELPING TO CONNECT THESE GROUPS TO MARKETS AND INSTITUTIONAL BUYERS THROUGH ONLINE TRADING PLATFORMS. IN JUNE, A FEDERATION OF PRODUCER GROUPS IN THE BIHAR REGION WAS ABLE TO PROCURE OVER 1,000 TONS OF MAIZE FROM NEARLY 300 SMALLHOLDERS. THESE GROUPS SAW A 15 PERCENT INCREASE IN THE PRICE FOR THEIR MAIZE. TECHNOSERVE ALSO LAUNCHED A PARTNERSHIP WITH J.P. MORGAN TO SUPPORT YOUTH ENTREPRENEURS IN MUMBAI, WHICH FOCUSED PROVIDING TRAINING AND EMPLOYMENT OPPORTUNITIES FOR 1,250 YOUTH.

column84: RJ in the Schools brings restorative justice principles to the administrators, teachers, families, and students of Monterey County Schools. These comprehensive and innovative programs address the needs of the entire school community.
column88: VORP is a mediation process which provides interested victims the opportunity to meet the offender in a safe and structured setting, with the goal of holding the offender directly accountable for their behavior and giving the victim an opportunity to have a voice in the process of reparation. The Merchant Accountability Panel (MAP) is an innovative application of the VORP process which focuses directly on the pervasive crime of juvenile shoplifting.
column96: The VIP program is geared toward helping offenders become more aware of the impact that crime has on victims. It is also focused on educating offenders to the long range harm caused to victims, families and community. The curriculum emphasizes victims and their rights as a central premise.

column84: OPRFCF provides a central resource for donors, professional financial advisors, student scholarships and non-profit organizations serving Oak Park and River Forest. For donors, we provide value and expertise in helping them explore and implement giving options. For non-profits serving our residents, we manage endowment funds and provide opportunities to apply for and receive grants. We also manage scholarship programs for several of our fundholders.
column88: Success of All Youth (SAY) is a community collective impact effort addressing the social & emotional, academic, and health & safety needs of youth from cradle to career. One full time director and one part time communications manager facilitated and supported the work of the initiative. (includes direct salary/benefit and other operations costs)
column96: The Foundation offered 10 Impact Excellence Seminars in 2015 which were attended by 229 participants from 60 local nonprofits. These seminars covered a range of topics including, Funding for Impact, Impact Measurement and Evaluation, Enhancing your Volunteer Program, How to Talk to your Donors about your Endowment and a Board Boot Camp. Furthermore (6) local nonprofits received technical assistance and consulting support in 2015/2016 to address key needs related to measuring the impact of their work. This technical assistance was provided to organizations working in different sectors; and across varying operational contexts including partnerships and mergers. Results of the technical assistance include the development of a clear framework of outcomes and indicators for all participating organizations; and demonstration of the value and impact of program activities which informs program design, marketing, communications and fundraising efforts. (does not include salary/benefit costs)

column84: CLIMATE CHANGE: IN 2015 SBC WORKED WITH NUMEROUS COMMUNITIES ON DEVELOPING GREENHOUSE GAS INVENTORIES; ENERGY ACTION PLANS; CLIMATE ACTION PLANS; REGIONAL CLIMATE ADAPTATION AND MITIGATION STRATEGIES; AND INCORPORATING SIERRA NEVADA GOALS INTO STATE POLICIES RELATED TO CLIMATE, WATER AND FIRE. SBC IMPLEMENTED PROGRAMS DESIGNED TO IMPROVE ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND IMPROVE ACCESS TO CAPITAL TO FINANCE ENERGY EFFICIENCY FOR SMALL AND MEDIUM SIZED BUSINESSES, NON PROFIT ORGANIZATIONS, AND MUNICIPAL FACILITIES. OUR ENERGY SERVICES PROJECTS WORK DIRECTLY WITH SIERRA BUSINESSES AND LOCAL GOVERNMENTS, LINKING SUSTAINABLE ECONOMIES TO THRIVING COMMUNITIES THROUGH ENERGY EFFICIENCY RETROFITS, GREEN HOUSE GAS EMISSION INVENTORIES, AND CLIMATE ACTION PLANNING. OUR ENERGY EFFICIENCY TEAM SERVED 245 CUSTOMERS IN 2015 SAVING 3.5 MILLION KWH OF ELECTRICITY, DISTRIBUTED $800,000 IN REBATES, AND REDUCED GREENHOUSE GAS EMISSIONS BY OVER 600 METRIC TONS. SBC ALSO HOSTED THE SIERRA CLIMATE ADAPTATION AND MITIGATION PARTNERHSIP, A COLLABORATIVE PROJECT WITH THE GOVERNORS OFFICE OF PLANNING AND RESEARCH AND THE ALLIANCE OF REGIONAL COLLABORATIVES FOR CLIMATE ADAPTATION WITH MORE THAN 30 LOCAL PARTNERS FOCUSED ON PREPARING THE REGION FOR CLIMATE CHANGE. OUR CLIMATE PLANNING TEAM DEVELEOPED 4 GREENHOUSE GAS INVENTORIES AND 3 ENERGY ACTION PLANS IN 2015.ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT: THE SIERRA SMALL BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT CENTER SERVING RURAL NORTHEASTERN CALIFORNIA WITH BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT AND IMPROVEMENT SERVICES, IMPROVING ACCESS TO CAPITAL, LINKING TO JOB TRAINING SERVICES, AND COUNSELING BUSINESSES ON INCORPORATING SOCIAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL VALUES. THE SIERRA SMALL BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT COMPLETED ITS FIRST FULL YEAR OF ACTIVITIES IN Q4 2015; SERVED 223 CUSTOMERS, PROVIDED 1276 HOURS OF COUNSELING, CONDUCTED 41 WORKSHOPS AND LEVERAGED $10.4 MILLION IN NEW CAPITAL IN THE REGION. SBC ALSO CONTINUED DEVELOPMENT AND HOSTING OF THE REGIONAL GEOTOURISM WEB PLATFORM GARNERING MORE THAN 600,000 VIRTUAL VISITS TO THE REGION AND BEGAN HOSTING THE LAKE TAHOE WATER TRAIL A COLLABORATIVE PROJECT TO BOOST VISTORSHIP AND SAFTEY ALONG THE SHORES OF LAKE TAHOE. SBC FISCALLY SPONSORED THE START UP OF THE TAHOE FOOD HUB AND THE TRUCKEE MAKERS SPACE. LARGE LANDSCAPE CONSERVATION; SBC CONTINUED TO WORK ON THREE KEYSTONE LANDCONSERVATION INTITIATIVES INCLUDING THE NORTHERN SIERRA PARTNERSHIP, SOUTHERN SIERRA PARTNERSHIP, AND PLACER LEGACY, LEADING TO THE DIRECT PROTECTION THROUGH CONSERVATION EASEMENTS OF WORKING LANDSCAPES AND FORESTS IN THE SIERRA NEVADA. SBC AND PARTNERS PROTECTED MORE THAN 12,000 ACRES OF LAND THROUGH EITHER DIRECT PURCHASES OR CONSERVATION EASEMENT, ATTRACTING MORE THAN $20,000,000 IN DIRECT INVESTMENT IN THE REGION.
column88: EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE: ALL SBC PROJECTS ARE DESIGNED TO MODEL NEW BEHAVIOR AND TO MEASURE AND DEMONSTRATE THE BENEFITS OF NEW BEHAVIOR THROUGH ON-THE-GROUNDIMPLEMENTATION. WE ONLY TAKE ON PROJECTS THAT MODEL NEW APPROACHES TO SOLVINGDIFFICULT TO SOLVE SOCIAL, ENVIRONMENTAL AND ECONOMIC PROBLEMS. EACH PROJECT HAS A BUILT IN OUTREACH AND PUBLIC EDUCATION COMPONENT DESIGNED TO MEET OUR EDUCATIONAL PURPOSE.
column96: PLANNING: SBC CONTINUES TO HELP COMMUNITIES PLAN FOR FUTURE SOCIAL, NATURAL AND ECONOMIC SUSTAINABILITY THROUGH IMPROVED COMMUNITY PLANNING INCLUDING PROVIDING INFORMATION TO ASSIST JURISDICTIONS WITH GENERAL PLANS, SPECIFIC PLANS, COMMUNITY PLANS, ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT PLANS, TRANSPORTATION AND INFRASTRUCTURE PLANS, IMPROVING ACCESS TO AFFORDABLE HOUSING, AND COMMUNITY VISIONING. IN 2015 SBC HOSTED MEETINGS DESIGNED TO IMPLEMENT THE CA ECONOMY SUMMIT ACTION PLAN ON HOUSING, ACCESS TO CAPITAL AND WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT. SBC AND PARTNERS HAVE PARTICIPATED IN COMMUNITY PLANNING PROCESSES IN 6 COMMUNITIES AND DEVELOPED GRANT APPLICATIONS FOR AFFORDABLE HOUSING FUNDING IN TWO COMMUNITIES LEVERAGING MORE THAN $8 MILLION IN FUNDING.

column40: SUSTAINABLE CONSERVATION (THE ORGANIZATION) PARTNERS WITH BUSINESS, AGRICULTURE, AND GOVERNMENT TO FIND PRACTICAL WAYS THE PRIVATE SECTOR CAN PROTECT AIR AND WATER, AS WELL AS ENSURE HEALTHY ECOSYSTEMS. THE ORGANIZATION'S WORK SPANS RURAL AND URBAN ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES, RANGING FROM IMPROVING WATER QUALITY IN DAIRY FARMING, TO PROMOTING THE GROWING AND SELLING OF NON-INVASIVE PLANTS IN CALIFORNIA'S HORTICULTURAL INDUSTRY, TO PARTNERING WITH FARMERS IN CALIFORNIA'S SAN JOAQUIN VALLEY ON SUSTAINABLE-GROUNDWATER SOLUTIONS. THE ORGANIZATION WORKS WITH FARMERS TO IDENTIFY WAYS THEY CAN PROTECT THE ENVIRONMENT, IMPROVE THEIR BOTTOM LINES, AND KEEP THEIR LAND IN PRODUCTION. IT ALSO WORKS TO OVERCOME THE TIME, COMPLEXITY, AND COST ASSOCIATED WITH VOLUNTARY HABITAT RESTORATION ON PRIVATE LAND. FINALLY, THE ORGANIZATION WORKS WITH BUSINESSES AND GOVERNMENT AGENCIES TO ENSURE A MORE SUSTAINABLE WATER SUPPLY FOR THE STATE.
column80: SUSTAINABLE CONSERVATION HELPS CALIFORNIA THRIVE BY UNITING PEOPLE TO SOLVE THE TOUGHEST CHALLENGES FACING OUR LAND, AIR AND WATER. EVERY DAY, WE BRING TOGETHER BUSINESS, LANDOWNERS AND GOVERNMENT TO STEWARD THE RESOURCES THAT WE ALL DEPEND ON IN WAYS THAT MAKE ECONOMIC SENSE. BECAUSE WE KNOW THAT COMMON GROUND IS CALIFORNIA'S MOST IMPORTANT RESOURCE.
column84: DAIRIES: WE WORK WITH CALIFORNIA DAIRY PRODUCERS TO PROMOTE MANAGEMENT PRACTICES THAT ARE MORE PROTECTIVE OF WATER AND AIR QUALITY AND WORK ECONOMICALLY. IN 2015, WE PILOTED AN INNOVATIVE LIQUID MANURE DRIP IRRIGATION SYSTEM THAT APPLIES NUTRIENTS MORE PRECISELY TO CROP ROOT ZONES, WHICH IN TURN LEADS TO SIGNIFICANTLY LESS NITROGEN LEACHING INTO GROUNDWATER SUPPLIES. WE ALSO BEGAN A FEASIBILITY STUDY ON A MARKET FOR COMPOSTED DAIRY MANURE TO BE USED AS A VALUABLE SOIL AMENDMENT FOR OTHER FARMING CROPS. TO IMPROVE AIR QUALITY IN THE SAN JOAQUIN VALLEY, WE PROMOTED LOW-INTENSITY CULTIVATION PRACTICES, OR "CONSERVATION TILLAGE", TO REDUCE DUST AND DIESEL EMISSIONS FROM TRACTORS. WE ESTABLISHED A CONSERVATION TILLAGE EQUIPMENT RENTAL PROGRAM THROUGH WHICH 11 FARMERS ON 2,145 ACRES HAVE IMPLEMENTED THE PRACTICE TO DATE.
column88: WATER: WATER IS IN SHORT SUPPLY IN CALIFORNIA. SUSTAINABLE CONSERVATION EVALUATES NEW WATER MANAGEMENT APPROACHES SO FARMS, THE ENVIRONMENT, AND COMMUNITIES HAVE THE WATER THEY NEED FOR YEARS TO COME. WE WORK IN THE SAN JOAQUIN VALLEY TO EVALUATE AND PROMOTE THE CAPTURE OF STORM WATER FLOOD FLOWS ON ACTIVE FARMLAND TO REPLENISH GROUNDWATER AQUIFERS, CALIFORNIA'S MOST IMPORTANT DROUGHT RESERVE. AS A RESULT OF OUR EXTENSIVE OUTREACH, 23 GROWERS HAVE OFFERED 130 DEMONSTRATION SITES, REPRESENTING 10 DIFFERENT CROPS AND ALMOST 15,000 ACRES, ALLOWING US THE OPPORTUNITY TO COLLECT MONITORING DATA TO FURTHER PROVE THIS APPROACH AND LAY THE GROUNDWORK TO BRING THIS STRATEGY TO SCALE WHEN SIGNIFICANT FLOOD FLOWS RETURN TO CALIFORNIA.
column96: ACCELERATING RESTORATION: SUSTAINABLE CONSERVATION MAKES IT EASIER FOR LANDOWNERS TO STEWARD NATURAL RESOURCES. WE WORK WITH THE LEGISLATURE AND GOVERNMENT AGENCIES TO SIMPLIFY THE PERMITTING PROCESS SO LANDOWNERS CAN COMPLETE PROJECTS THAT RESTORE STREAM, REBUILD HABITAT, AND REDUCE SOIL EROSION IN A FEW MONTHS RATHER THAN A FEW YEARS. IN 2015, WE WORKED WITH NOAA FISHERIES TO ISSUE A FORMAL SOUTH COAST PROGRAMMATIC BIOLOGICAL OPINION TO MATCH THE PROGRAMMATIC BIOLOGICAL OPINION IN PLACE FOR THE CENTRAL AND NORTH COASTS - COVERING THE ENTIRE CALIFORNIA COAST WITH SIMPLIFIED PERMITTING BY THIS AGENCY.

column84: ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT - COUNSELORS PROVIDE TRAINING, TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND LENDING TO SMALL BUSINESSES AND MICRO-ENTERPRISES. AS THE NATION'S LARGEST SBA MICRO-LOAN INTERMEDIARY, JUSTINE PETERSEN BORROWS MONEY DIRECTLY FROM THE SBA AND ORIGINATES MICRO-ENTERPRISE LOANS UNDER $50,000 IN ACCORDANCE WITH ITS OWN UNDERWRITING GUIDELINES TO SMALL BUSINESS OWNERS THAT MAY NOT BE ABLE TO SECURE CAPITAL ELSEWHERE. JUSTINE PETERSEN PARTICIPATES IN THE USDA INTERMEDIARY RELENDING PROGRAM FOR ITS RURAL LENDING. GREAT RIVERS COMMUNITY CAPITAL ALSO ORIGINATES MICRO-ENTERPRISE AND SMALL BUSINESS LOANS. GEOGRAPHICALLY, JUSTINE PETERSEN/ GREAT RIVERS CURRENTLY OFFER MICROENTERPRISE/ SMALL BUSINESS LOANS IN SEVENTY-THREE ILLINOIS AND TWENTY EIGHT KANSAS COUNTIES AND THE ENTIRE STATE OF MISSOURI. IN 2015, JUSTINE PETERSEN PROVIDED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND TRAINING TO OVER 2,500 ENTREPRENEURS AND ORIGINATED $11MM IN OVER 860 MICRO- AND SMALLBUSINESS LOANS. JUSTINE PETERSEN ALSO ADMINISTERS A CONTRACTOR LOANFUND TO MEET THE NEEDS OF SMALL AND MINORITY CONTRACTORS WHO LACK THEFINANCIAL CAPACITY TO SUCCESSFULLY BID, ACCEPT AND CARRY OUT THE WORKOF LARGE SCALE PROPERTY DEVELOPMENT CONTRACTS. IN 2015, JUSTINEPETERSEN ORIGINATED $2.7MM IN NEARLY 100 CONTRACTOR LOANS.
column88: HOUSING - AS A HUD CERTIFIED HOUSING COUNSELING AGENCY, COUNSELORS ASSIST LOW- TO MODERATE-INCOME FAMILIES AND INDIVIDUALS TO ADDRESS CREDIT AND OTHER BARRIERS TO PURCHASING OR REFINANCING A HOME THROUGH CREDIT BUILDING STRATEGIES AND PRODUCTS, BUDGETING, FINANCIAL EDUCATION, LOAN COUNSELING AND HOMEBUYER EDUCATION AND ASSIST HOMEOWNERS STRUGGLING TO PAY THEIR MORTGAGES WITH FINANCIAL COUNSELING AND NEGOTIATION WITH THEIR LENDER. IN 2015, ONE HUNDRED AND TWENTY-ONE (121) FAMILIES PURCHASED HOMES AFTER PARTICIPATING IN JUSTINE PETERSEN'S HOMEBUYER COUNSELING AND EDUCATION AND EIGHTY-FIVE (85) FAMILIES IN FORECLOSURE RECEIVED ASSISTANCE.
column96: SAVINGS - JUSTINE PETERSEN BELIEVES THAT A STRONG CREDIT PROFILE IS ONE'S MOST IMPORTANT FINANCIAL ASSET. COUNSELORS TEACH HOW TO BUILD AND MAINTAIN A STRONG CREDIT PROFILE. IN 2015, ONE THOUSAND, TWO HUNDRED NINETEEN (1,219) LOW- AND MODERATE-INCOME INDIVIDUALS PARTICIPATED IN JUSTINE PETERSEN CREDIT BUILDING SERVICES. IN 2015, THE AVERAGE FICO CREDIT SCORE INCREASE AFTER SIX MONTHS OF PARTICIPATION WAS FIFTY (50) POINTS. AS A LEADER IN THE CREDIT BUILDING AND FINANCIAL CAPABILITY FIELD, JUSTINE PETERSEN TEACHES FINANCIAL COUNSELORS ACROSS THE COUNTRY HOW TO OFFER CREDIT BUILDING SERVICES. IN 2015, JUSTINE PETERSENTRAINED THREE HUNDRED AND TWENTY-TWO FINANCIAL COUNSELORS FROM ORGANIZATIONS IN INDIANA, KENTUCKY, MINNESOTA, KANSAS, MISSOURI, CALIFORNIA, MASSACHUSETTS, ILLINOIS, WISCONSIN, PENNSYLVANIA, MICHIGAN, OKLAHOMA, IOWA, AND RHODE ISLAND ON ITS CREDIT BUILDING METHOD AND LAUNCHED THE JP TRAINING CENTER (JPTRAININGCENTER.ORG)

WE HAVE PROTECTED TENS OF THOUSANDS OF ACRES OF ONCE THREATENED WILDLANDS AND HELPED RESTORE SPECIES BACK FROM THE BRINK OF EXTINCTION, THE GRAY WOLF, FOR EXAMPLE. column80: CHESTERTON ACADEMY OF THE HOLY FAMILY IS A PRIVATE HIGH SCHOOL GUIDED BY THE TRUTHS OF THE CATHOLIC FAITH AND LOYAL TO THE MAGISTERIUM. ITS GOAL IS TO PROVIDE AN AFFORDABLE CLASSICAL CURRICULUM STEEPED IN TRADITION, AND AUGMENTED BY THE SOCRATIC METHOD IN ORDER TO CULTIVATE ITS STUDENTS BOTH SPIRITUALLY AND ACADEMICALLY. AS A SCHOOL, IT WILL REINFORCE THE ROLE OF PARENTS AS PRIMARY EDUCATORS OF THEIR CHILDREN AND PROMOTE THE IMPORTANCE OF THE FAMILY AS THE BASIC BUILDING BLOCK OF A CIVILIZED SOCIETY. FAITH AND REASON WILL BE INTERWOVEN IN EVERY CLASS AND JOY SHALL BE PRESENT FROM THE ENTRANCE HYMN OF THE DAILY MASS TO THE CLOSING BELL OF THE SCHOOL DAY FOR THE GREATER GLORY OF GOD. CHESTERTON ACADEMY OF THE HOLY FAMILY ADMITS STUDENTS OF ANY RACE, COLOR, NATIONAL ORIGIN, AND ETHNIC ORIGIN TO ALL THE RIGHTS, PRIVILEGES, PROGRAMS, AND ACTIVITIES GENERALLY ACCORDED OR MADE AVAILABLE TO STUDENTS AT THE SCHOOL. IT DOES NOT DISCRIMINATE ON THE BASIS OF RACE, COLOR, NATIONAL ORIGIN, AND ETHNI

column40: PCHAS PROVIDES CHRIST-CENTERED CARE AND SUPPORT TO CHILDREN AND FAMILIES IN NEED.
column80: PRESBYTERIAN CHILDREN'S HOMES AND SERVICES PROVIDES A VARIETY OF CHRIST-CENTERED CARE AND SUPPORT TO CHILDREN AND FAMILIES IN NEED.
column84: FOSTER CARE: THIS PROGRAM SERVES CHILDREN FROM INFANCY TO AGE 17 AT THE TIME OF ADMISSION. PCHAS STRUCTURES ITS THERAPEUTIC SERVICES TO HELP CHILDREN WHO EXPERIENCE SOCIAL & EMOTIONAL DIFFICULTIES, DEVELOPMENTAL DELAYS, LEARNING PROBLEMS & BEHAVIORAL CHALLENGES. THE PROGRAM IS NOT APPROPRIATE FOR CHILDREN WHOSE NEEDS ARE SO INTENSE THEY REQUIRE REGULAR 24-HOUR AWAKE SUPERVISION.
column88: GROUP HOMES: PCHAS OPERATES 8 GROUP HOMES IN TWO TEXAS LOCATIONS - ITASCA & WAXAHACHIE. EACH HOME SERVES 6-8 CHILDREN BETWEEN THE AGES OF 5 & 17. OUR TRAINED STAFF SERVE AS PARENTS TO PROVIDE A NURTURING ENVIRONMENT FOR CHILDREN TO PRACTICE POSITIVE BEHAVIORS AND HEALTHY FAMILY RELATIONSHIPS. CHILDREN RECEIVE SPIRITUAL GUIDANCE & CHRISTIAN NURTURE THROUGH PRAYER, BIBLE STUDY, AND PARTICIPATION IN THE WORSHIP & LIFE OF LOCAL PRESBYTERIAN CHURCH (USA) CONGREGATIONS. THE CHILDREN ATTEND LOCAL SCHOOLS & RECEIVE DAILY SUPERVISED STUDY TIME & SPECIALIZED TUTORING AS NEEDED. IN ADDITION, PCHAS PROVIDES YOUTH IN CARE WITH COUNSELING TO HELP THEM OVERCOME THE TRAUMAS THEY HAVE FACED IN THEIR YOUNG LIVES.
column96: CHILD & FAMILY: THE GOAL OF THIS PROGRAM IS TO ADDRESS ISSUES BEFORE A CRISIS RESULTS IN OUT-OF-HOME PLACEMENT OF CHILDREN. THIS PROGRAM DEALS WITH THESE ISSUES WHILE WORKING TO KEEP FAMILIES TOGETHER. WE HELP REMOVE THE BARRIERS THAT CAN PREVENT FAMILIES FROM RECEIVING THE SERVICES THEY NEED. CURRENTLY, THE PROGRAM IS IN THE FOLLOWING CITIES: ABILENE, AUSTIN, CORPUS CHRISTI, CORSICANA, DALLAS, FORT WORTH, HOUSTON, KILGORE, LONGVIEW, SAN ANTONIO, TEMPLE, WICHITA FALLS, MIDLAND, LUBBOCK, HURST, AND WEATHERFORD, TX AND BATON ROUGE AND NEW ORLEANS, LA.

column40: ADVANCING COMMUNITY SUPPORT AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR PEOPLE LIVING WITH DISABILITIES.
column80: ST. JOHN'S COMMUNITY SERVICES-PENNSYLVANIA'S MISSION IS TO ADVANCE COMMUNITY SUPPORT AND OPPORTUNITIES TO PEOPLE LIVING WITH DISABILITIES. THE ORGANIZATION PROVIDES OPPORTUNITIES TO HELP CHILDREN AND ADULTS WITH DISABILITIES SUCCESSFULLY BECOME A PART OF THE COMMUNITY OF THEIR CHOICE THROUGH SUPPORT PROVIDED BY DEDICATED STAFF. SOMETIMES SUCCESSES ARE MEASURED IN IMPERCEPTIBLE WAYS - FROM AN INDIVIDUAL'S FIRST STEP INTO THE COMMUNITY, TO AN EMPLOYER'S GREATER APPRECIATION FOR THE TALENTS OF PEOPLE WITH DISABILITIES, TO STAFF MEMBERS TAKING OWNERSHIP TO CREATE A MORE EFFECTIVE PROCESS TO SUPPORT INDIVIDUALS, TO SUCCESSFUL ADVOCACY OF GOVERNMENT FOR GREATER FINANCIAL SUPPORT AND ACCESS. OUR MANY VOICES UNITE UNDER ONE MISSION AND MEET OPPORTUNITY WITH ACTION TO CREATE SOCIAL CHANGE AND ENABLE PEOPLE TO LIVE THEIR DREAMS AND CONTRIBUTE TO THEIR COMMUNITIES.
column84: ST. JOHN'S COMMUNITY SERVICES - PENNSYLVANIA IS A SUBSIDIARY CORPORATION OF ST. JOHN'S COMMUNITY SERVICES. THE PARENT CORPORATION IS SEPARATELY INCORPORATED IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA AND GOVERNED BY A VOLUNTEER BOARD OF TRUSTEES. EACH OF THE SUBSIDIARIES, INCLUDING SJCS-PA, HAS A LOCAL VOLUNTEER BOARD OF DIRECTORS AND IS SUPERVISED BY LOCAL LEADERSHIP, WITH ADMINISTRATIVE OFFICES LOCATED IN THE STATE OF PENNSYLVANIA WHERE THE SUBSIDIARY IS INCORPORATED. SJSC-PA CONTRACTS TO USE THE COPYRIGHTED NAME "ST. JOHN'S COMMUNITY SERVICES AND PURCHASES VARIOUS ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES FROM THE PARENT CORPORATION. AS A CONDITION OF THE CONTRACT, THE PARENT CORPORATION ESTABLISHES AND MONITORS SERVICE QUALITY STANDARDS AND THE SUBSIDIARY ACCEPTS THESE SERVICE STANDARDS.THE ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE THAT THE PARENT CORPORATION PROVIDES INCLUDE: ACCOUNTING, CASH MANAGEMENT, EVALUATION AND STRATEGIC PLANNING, COMMUNICATION AND INFORMATION DISSEMINATION, HUMAN RESOURCES, INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY, QUALITY ASSURANCE, CORPORATE COMPLIANCE AND PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT. EACH OF THESE SUPPORT SERVICES IS INDIVIDUALLY TAILORED TO MEET THE UNIQUE NEEDS OF THIS SUBSIDIARY CORPORATION AND ITS DISTINCTIVE CULTURAL AS WELL AS FINANCIAL STATUS. THESE SERVICES ASSIST SJCS-PA TO MEET THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE CONTRACTS, LAWS AND REGULATIONS UNDER WHICH IT OPERATES. SJCS-PA OPERATES UNDER ITS OWN OPERATING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES AND LOCAL LEADERSHIP. ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT SERVICES ARE BILLED BY THE PARENT CORPORATION, ST. JOHN'S COMMUNITY SERVICES, TO THE SUBSIDIARY CORPORATION, SJCS-PA, AT A LOW FIXED RATE CONSISTENT WITH NATIONAL STANDARDS.TO FURTHER THE AGENCY'S MISSION OF ADVANCING COMMUNITY SUPPORT AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR PEOPLE LIVING WITH DISABILITIES, THE PARENT CORPORATION SETS QUALITY STANDARDS CONSISTENT WITH THE MISSION THAT MUST BE MET BY THE SJCS-PA SUBSIDIARY IN THE PROVISION OF SERVICES. THOSE SERVICES MUST FOSTER INCLUSION, SELF DIRECTION, ECONOMIC SELF-SUFFICIENCY, RELATIONSHIP DEVELOPMENT AND CHOICE. MEETING AND MAINTAINING THESE STANDARDS IS A REQUIREMENT FOR THE CONTINUATION OF THE ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT CONTRACT AND USE OF THE CORPORATE NAME. THE PARENT CORPORATION ALSO PROVIDES TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND TRAINING TO THE SJCS-PA SUBSIDIARY CORPORATION TO FACILITATE THE ATTAINMENT OF THESE ESTABLISHED STANDARDS. PEOPLE RECEIVING SERVICES THROUGH THE ST. JOHN'S SUBSIDIARY MUST MEET LOCAL FUNDING SOURCES AND THE SUBSIDIARY'S UNIQUE ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS FOR EACH SPECIFIC SERVICE.TYPES OF COMMUNITY SUPPORTS AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR PEOPLE LIVING WITH DISABILITIES THAT SJCS-PA PROVIDED DURING THE 2015 FISCAL YEAR INCLUDED EMPLOYMENT SERVICES AND COMMUNITY PARTICIPATION. THE TOTAL NUMBER OF PEOPLE WITH DISABILITIES SUPPORTED IN FY 2015 WAS AS FOLLOWS: - EMPLOYMENT SERVICES: 35 ADULTS PARTICIPATED IN JOB DEVELOPMENT, COACHING, PLACEMENT AND ON-GOING SUPPORT IN JOBS WORKING ALONGSIDE EMPLOYEES WITHOUT DISABILITIES.- COMMUNITY PARTICIPATION: NO ADULTS PARTICIPATED IN THIS NEW SJCS-PA SERVICE THAT PROVIDES VOLUNTEER AND COMMUNITY EXPLORATION, SKILL DEVELOPMENT AND VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES.

column40: Goodwill Specialty Services creates employment and job-training opportunities for people who have significant disabilities or other challenges to employment by providing contract work for businesses; federal, state, and local government; and other community partners.
column80: Develop job skills and employment opportunities for people with disabilities and other vocational disadvantages, striving to increase the self-sufficiency of the corporations's program participants.
column84: FEDERAL CONTRACTS - Goodwill Specialty Services Inc (GSSI) provides employment opportunities through contracts with separate government entities of the Federal Government. These are set aside contracts for people with severe disabilities through the Javits-Wagner-O'Day act of 1971. GSSI is currently engaged in custodial, postal services, and grounds maintenance contracts through this program. Employees are paid through a management and administrative services contract with Goodwill Industries Inc. In 2015, GSSI was responsible for over 3,000,000 square feet of buildings for various janitorial contracts at Offutt Airforce Base, Stratcom, Zorinsky Federal building, and Denney Federal building in Lincoln. GSSI was also responsible for grounds maintenance at the VA hospital in Omaha, NE and Grand Island NE. GSSI also operates two postal contracts at Offutt Airforce Base serving over 1000 airmen and incoming personnel.
column88: OTHER CONTRACTS - GSSI's commercial services division provides job opportunities for individuals with barriers to employment. Current contracts include commercial bus cleaning for MAT bus in Omaha, pressure washing for MAT bus in Omaha, custodial services for private businesses, and grounds maintenance for residential and commercial customers. Individuals are provided full or part time employment depending on their personal preference. Training relative to a job requirement is provided to ensure personnel are given an opportunity to understand what is expected of them and to provide a path for professional growth.

column40: Tides Center accelerates the pace of social change, working with innovative partners to solve society's toughest problems.
column80: Vision: Tides Center envisions a world of shared prosperity and social justice founded on equality & human rights; a sustainable environment; healthy individuals and communities; and quality education.Mission: Tides Center accelerates the pace of social change, working with innovative partners to solve society's toughest problems.Approach: We cross boundaries and link sectors, communities and cultures.We act with empathy and respect.We engage with those whose lives are affected.We embrace risk.We prioritize ideas that can scale.
column84: Equity:Within our largest area of impact, Tides projects work multilaterally to create more equal opportunity and equitable treatment for all. Projects focus on ethnic & racial equity, LGBTQ rights, economic opportunity, human rights policies, reproductive justice, protection of free speech, and increased civic engagement. Several programs worked to end homelessness by providing transitional housing and social services. Others advocated for issues such as the social and economic empowerment of women and girls, the replacement of our prison system for more practical local safety solutions, and the rights and protection of indigenous cultures.
column88: Education:In 2015, Tides projects enriched the education of youth living in local, underserved communities, focusing on areas such as leadership development, arts education, health and nutrition, family self-sufficiency, and STEM. Internationally, Tides projects improved science education for students in developing countries, provided training in effective condom usage to prevent the spread of HIV/AIDS, and provided training in emergency medicine and public health practices for healthcare providers. Other Tides projects instituted a variety of programs that ranged from educating men to advocate against domestic violence, to supporting qualified candidates searching for careers in higher education.
column96: Environment:In 2015, Tides projects worked in the areas of environmental sustainability, climate change, and sustainable agriculture practices. Programs worked at the local level to directly address environmental issues facing low-income, marginalized communities, as well as at the national and international levels in order to spearhead campaigns for responsible resource consumption and the preservation of our natural environment. Tides projects organized and supported the Farm to School food movement. Tides projects advocated for a more just, clean, and sustainable world from a variety of perspectives, from reducing environmental mercury exposure to developing regional food systems in order to enhance food security.

column84: SEE SCHEDULE O HEAD START AND EARLY HEAD START ARE FEDERALLY FUNDED PROGRAMS THAT OFFER FREE PRE-SCHOOL AND CHILD CARE SERVICES TO FAMILIES LIVING AT OR BELOW THE FEDERAL POVERTY GUIDELINES. SPECIAL CONSIDERATION IS GIVEN TO CHILDREN WITH DISABILITIES; LIVING IN FOSTER CARE, HOMELESS, OR RECEIVING PUBLIC ASSISTANCE. SERVICES INCLUDE CASE MANAGERS TO SUPPORT FAMILIES BE SUCCESSFUL. SERVICES INCLUDE PREGNANT WOMEN'S PROGRAM, HOMEBASED EARLY HEAD START SERVICES, CENTERED BASED EARLY HEAD START CLASSROOMS AND HEAD START PRESCHOOL CLASSROOMS. IN 2015 EARLY HEAD START SERVED 177 CHILDREN AND FAMILIES (INCLUDING PREGNANT WOMEN AND HOME BASED FAMILIES). THE TIPPECANOE COUNTY HEAD START PROGRAM SERVED 447 FAMILIES AND THE CARROLL, CLINTON, AND WHITE COUNTY PROGRAM SERVED 113 FAMILIES. OF THESE 7.7% WERE FOSTER CHILDREN, 3.9% WERE HOMELESS AND 4.9% WERE RECEIVING PUBLIC ASSISTANCE. THE ORGANIZATION RECEIVED 537,458 IN IN-KIND SUPPORT FROM THE COMMUNITY IN 2015.
column88: SEE SCHEDULE O FAMILY CENTERED SERVICES INCLUDES PROGRAMS AND SERVICES FUNDED BY STATE CONTRACTS AND GRANTS. IN BAUER'S COUNSELING DIVISION, MASTER'S LEVEL THERAPISTS AND BACHELOR'S LEVEL CASE MANAGERS PROVIDE SERVICES TO FAMILIES INVOLVED WITH THE CHILD WELFARE SYSTEM. SERVICES, PROVIDED IN-HOME, INCLUDING COUNSELING, CASE MANAGEMENT, SUPERVISED VISITATION AND SUPPORT FOR FATHERS. IN 2015 387 FAMILIES PARTICIPATED IN COUNSELING DIVISION SERVICES. OF THESE, 60% OF CHILDREN WERE REUNITED WITH OR REMAINED IN THE CARE OF THEIR PARENTS DURING THE CALENDAR YEAR. HOMEBUILDERS, A SHORT- TERM, INTENSIVE CASE MANAGEMENT PROGRAM FOR FAMILIES WITH INVOLVEMENT WITH CHILD WELFARE OR JUVENILE PROBATION, PROVIDED SERVICES TO 26 FAMILIES IN 2015 FOR A TOTAL OF 994 UNITS OF SERVICE. 95% OF FAMILIES WERE REUNITED OR HAD CHILDREN THAT REMAINED IN THE CARE OF THEIR PARENTS. COMMUNITY PARTNERS IS A CHILD ABUSE PREVENTION PROGRAM THAT OFFERS CASE MANAGEMENT SERVICES TO FAMILIES WITH CHILDREN. IN ADDITION TO CASE MANAGEMENT, THE PROGRAM CAN MEET CONCRETE NEEDS OF FAMILIES. IN 2015 MORE THAN 1,123 FAMILIES RECEIVED COMMUNITY PARTNERS SERVICES. THE PROGRAM PAID MORE THAN 117,000 FOR CONCRETE NEEDS (UTILITIES, BUYING BEDS, ETC.) AND COUNSELING FEES FOR PARTICIPANTS.
column96: YOUTH SERVICES INCLUDE THE REMAINDER OF THE ORGANIZATION'S PROGRAMS AND IN 2015 INCLUDED YOUTH DEVELOPMENT, TEEN COURT, AND SCHOOL COURT. DURING 2015, YOUTH DEVELOPMENT OFFERED BOTH AFTER SCHOOL AND SUMMER PROGRAMMING. THERE WERE 256 YOUTH WHO WERE MEMBERS OF THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM, RECEIVING MORE THAN 7,950 UNITS OF SERVICE THROUGHOUT THE YEAR. MEALS AND SNACKS WERE PROVIDED TO PARTICIPANTS DURING PROGRAMS. SERVICES INCLUDE HOMEWORK HELP, STEM AND ART ACTIVITIES, AND RECREATION. A READING PROGRAM AND BASKETBALL PROGRAM ALSO IS AVAILABLE TO PARTICIPANTS. THE SUMMER INCLUDES WEEKLY FIELD TRIPS.

column84: RESIDENTIAL PROGRAM SERVICES: 24-HOUR SAFE SHELTER - EMERGENCY SAFE HOUSING FOR VICTIMS OF CRISIS AND THEIR DEPENDENT CHILDREN. SHELTER IS HANDICAPPED ACCESSIBLE. column88: NON-RESIDENTIAL PROGRAM SERVICES: 1) 24-HOUR TELEPHONE HOTLINE - CRISIS INTERVENTION, EMOTIONAL SUPPORT, ADVOCACY, SHELTER ADMISSION, AND INFORMATION/REFERRAL. 2) ADVOCACY - 24-HOUR ASSISTANCE TO VICTIMS OF VIOLENCE THAT INCLUDES SAFETY PLANNING, CRIMINAL JUSTICE SYSTEM, MEDICAL, HOUSING, AND SOCIAL SERVICES. 3) COUNSELING - COUNSELING TO VICTIMS AND SECONDARY VICTIMS OF VIOLENCE AND CRIME. SERVICES ARE PROVIDED BY LAW ENFORCEMENT, THE DISTRICT ATTORNEY'S OFFICE, THE VICTIMS ASSISTANCE CENTER, CHILD PROTECTIVE SERVICES AND OUT TWO LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITIES.

column40: MISSION: STRENGTHENING THE EAST METRO AS AN INTEGRAL PART OF A THRIVING REGION.VISION: MINNESOTA...WHERE ALL COMMUNITIES AND PEOPLE THRIVE. VALUES: RESPECT, EXCELLENCE, INNOVATION, COLLABORATION, INTEGRITY AND EQUITY.SINCE 1940, THOUSANDS OF GENEROUS INDIVIDUALS COMMITTED TO THE SAINT PAUL AREA HAVE MADE CHARITABLE GIFTS TO THE SAINT PAUL FOUNDATION. TODAY, THE FOUNDATION IS THE STATE'S LARGEST COMMUNITY FOUNDATION. GUIDED BY THE LEGACY OF ITS EARLIEST DONORS, THE FOUNDATION HELPS DONORS ACHIEVE THEIR CHARITABLE GIVING GOALS AND HAVE LONG-LASTING IMPACT IN THE COMMUNITY. THE FOUNDATION IS AN AFFILIATE OF MINNESOTA PHILANTHROPY PARTNERS. LEARN MORE AT SAINTPAULFOUNDATION.ORG AND MNPARTNERS.ORG.
column80: SEE MISSION IN PART I, LINE 1
column84: WE WORK WITH DONORS, NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS AND LOCAL LEADERS TO IDENTIFY AND SUPPORT CRITICAL NEEDS IN THE GREATER SAINT PAUL AREA, INCLUDING DAKOTA, RAMSEY AND WASHINGTON COUNTIES. WE HELP DONORS ACHIEVE THEIR CHARITABLE GOALS AND ADDRESS CRITICAL ISSUES FACING COMMUNITIES AROUND THE STATE.THROUGH OUR GRANTMAKING, WE SUPPORT NONPROFITS DOING GREAT WORK IN SIX KEY AREAS: ECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY AND SECURITY; EDUCATION AND TRAINING; EXCELLENT QUALITY OF LIFE; HOUSING AND MOBILITY CHOICES; QUALITY AFFORDABLE HEALTH CARE; AND STRONG HUMAN SERVICES AND FAMILY SUPPORT. SEE SCHEDULE O FOR CONTINUATIONGRANTS ARE MADE FROM OUR UNRESTRICTED AND RESTRICTED FUNDS, THANKS TO THE GENEROSITY OF OUR DONORS, PAST AND PRESENT.
column88: THROUGH COMMUNITY INITIATIVES-INNOVATIVE AND RESPONSIVE PROGRAMS THAT DIRECTLY SEEK TO SOLVE COMMUNITY PROBLEMS-WE ARE ABLE TO SUPPORT AND ADDRESS TIMELY ISSUES. A SNAPSHOT OF OUR CURRENT WORK INCLUDES SUPPORT OF THE CENTRAL CORRIDOR FUNDERS COLLABORATIVE, WHICH WORKS TO ENSURE THAT THE NEW LIGHT RAIL TRANSIT LINE CONNECTING SAINT PAUL AND MINNEAPOLIS BENEFITS THE ENTIRE COMMUNITY; AN EARLY MATH PROGRAM CALLED NUMBERS WORK! THAT WORKS WITH CHILDREN AND THEIR FAMILIES AT HIGH RISK FOR ACADEMIC FAILURE TO GIVE THEM TOOLS FOR SUCCESS; AND THE MANAGEMENT IMPROVEMENT FUND WHICH HELPS HUNDREDS OF NONPROFITS INVEST IN LONG-TERM PLANNING, STRENGTHEN THEIR OPERATIONS AND BOLSTER THEIR CAPACITY TO SERVE THE COMMUNITY. VISIT SAINTPAULFOUNDATION.ORG TO LEARN ABOUT ALL OF OUR COMMUNITY INITIATIVES.
column96: WE SUPPORT EFFECTIVE GRANTMAKING AND PROVIDE ADMINISTRATIVE SERVICES FOR A WIDE VARIETY OF FUNDS AND FOUNDATIONS SERVING MINNESOTA AND THE EAST METRO AREA, INCLUDING DAKOTA, RAMSEY AND WASHINGTON COUNTIES.

column40: THE MISSION OF TALL TIMBERS RESEARCH, INC. IS TO FOSTER EXEMPLARY LAND STEWARDSHIP THROUGH RESEARCH, CONSERVATION AND EDUCATION.
column80: THE MISSION OF TALL TIMBERS RESEARCH,INC. IS TO FOSTER EXEMPLARY LAND STEWARDSHIP THROUGH RESEARCH, CONSERVATION AND EDUCATION.OUR PRIMARY RESEARCH FOCUS IS THE ECOLOGY OF FIRE AND NATURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT INCLUDING BOBWHITE QUAIL AND OTHER WILDLIFE IN THE SOUTHEASTERN COASTAL PLAIN. OUR CONSERVATION EFFORTS ARE DEDICATED TO HELPING PROTECT THE DISTINCTIVE RED HILLS LANDSCAPE OF SOUTH GEORGIA AND NORTH FLORIDA, AND ITS TRADITIONAL LAND USES. OUR EDUCATION PROGRAM TRANSFERS RESEARCH AND CONSERVATION INFORMATION FOR RESOURCE MANAGEMENT.DEFINING EXEMPLARY LAND STEWARDSHIP EXEMPLARY LAND STEWARDSHIP (ELS) BALANCES ECOLOGICAL VALUES AND ECONOMIC UTILITY WITHIN A FRAMEWORK OF LONG-TERM CONSERVATION. THE FOUNDATION OF ELS ON UPLAND HABITATS IN THE RED HILLS IS THE FREQUENT USE OF FIRE TO ACCOMMODATE MANAGEMENT FOR BOBWHITE QUAIL, SELECTION TIMBER HARVEST, AND OTHER TRADITIONAL LAND USES. SCENIC, OPEN MULTI-AGED FOREST STRUCTURES ARE FUNDAMENTAL TO ELS.
column84: QUAIL MANAGEMENT RESEARCH MONITORED RADIO-TAGGED BOBWHITES AS PART OF STUDIES ON POPULATION DYNAMICS ON NORTHERN BOBWHITE IN GA, FL, SC, NC, AND NJ; TRANSLOCATED WILD BOBWHITES TO 5 SITES ACROSS THE SOUTHEASTERN AND MID-ATLANTIC U.S. TO ESTABLISH NEW POPULATIONS AND CONDUCT RESEARCH IN RELATION TO SUCH; WE CONTINUED OUR STUDIES ON BOBWHITE SURVIVAL RATES IN RELATION TO COVER MANAGEMENT, COVEY MOVEMENTS IN RELATION TO HUNTING PRESSURE, AND WILD TURKEY MOVEMENTS IN RELATION TO SUPPLEMENTAL FEEDING; CONDUCTED 2 BOBWHITE DOG FIELD TRIALS, PUBLISHED 2 MANAGEMENT NEWSLETTERS, MONITORED BOBWHITE ON COLLABORATIVE FOREST RESTORATION LANDSCAPE PROJECT ON OSCEOLA NATIONAL FOREST AND ON 4 SITES IN FLORIDA ON PUBLIC LANDS TOTALING 100,000 ACRES.
column88: STAFF MADE 35 SCIENTIFIC PRESENTATIONS AT CONFERENCES, SEMINARS AND WORKSHOPS, AND REACHED OVER 4300 PROFESSIONALS THROUGH 156 OUTREACH ACTIVITIES. PUBLISHED 12 SCIENTIFIC MANUSCRIPTS RELATED TO FIRE ECOLOGY AND MANAGEMENT; CONTINUED BEHAVIOR ECOLOGY OF BROWN-HEADED NUTHATCHES; CONTINUED PRESCRIBED FIRE PM RESEARCH MONITORING AND MODELLING, CONTINUED LONG-TERM FIRE PLOT RESEARCH IN NATIVE GROUND COVER, COMPLETED HISTORICAL RECORDS FOR THE FIRE USE ON OLD GROWTH FORESTS, ESTABLISHED AN ON-LINE HERBARIUM RESOURCE, HOSTED REGIONAL MESSAGING WORKSHOP FOR PRESCRIBED FIRE, TRAINED FIRE PROFESSIONALS ON PRESCRIBED FIRE METHODS.
column96: IN 2015, TALL TIMBERS CLOSED ON A 1,389 ACRE CONSERVATION EASEMENT FOR HICKORY GROVE PLANTATION IN MACON COUNTY, GEORGIA. IN ADDITION, TALL TIMBERS SUCCESSFULLY RECEIVED UNANIMOUS SUPPORT FROM THE SUWANNEE RIVER WATER MANAGEMENT DISTRICT (SRWMD) TO START THE LAND ACQUISITION PROCESS FOR SAVING A MATURE GROWTH CYPRESS TRACT ADJACENT TO SNEADS SMOKEHOUSE RECREATIONAL AREA ALONG THE AUCILLA RIVER IN JEFFERSON COUNTY, FLORIDA. A GOPHER TORTOISE SPECIES SURVEY WAS CONDUCTED IN THE GREATER RED HILLS REGION. THE EIGHT-MONTH SURVEY EXAMINED 34,000 ACRES OF PRIVATE LAND, AND THE FINDINGS CONCLUDED THAT THE REGION SUPPORTS AN ESTIMATED 23,000 TORTOISES, REFLECTING A HEALTHY POPULATION. FINALLY, TALL TIMBERS JOINED THE LAND TRUST ALLIANCE IN AN OUTREACH EFFORT TO SECURE PASSAGE OF THE FEDERAL ENHANCED TAX INCENTIVES FOR DONATED CONSERVATION EASEMENTS, WHICH WAS MADE PERMANENT AND SIGNED INTO LAW.

column40: TO PROTECT AND RESTORE THE REGION'S LAND AND WATER, CREATE GARDENS AND GREEN SPACES, AND PRESERVE FALLINGWATER.
column80: THE WESTERN PENNSYLVANIA CONSERVANCY PROTECTS AND RESTORES EXCEPTIONAL PLACES TO PROVIDE OUR REGION WITH CLEAN WATERS AND HEALTHY FORESTS, WILDLIFE AND NATURAL AREAS FOR THE BENEFIT OF PRESENT AND FUTURE GENERATIONS. THE CONSERVANCY CREATES GREEN SPACES AND GARDENS, CONTRIBUTING TO THE VITALITY OF OUR CITIES AND TOWNS, AND PRESERVES FALLINGWATER, A SYMBOL OF PEOPLE LIVING IN HARMONY WITH NATURE.
column84: LAND CONSERVATION PROGRAM: THIS PROGRAM INCLUDES LAND PROTECTION, LAND STEWARDSHIP, NATURAL HERITAGE AND CONSERVATION SCIENCE. THESE PROGRAMS FOCUS ON THE CONSERVATION AND RESTORATION OF THE REGION'S NATURAL AREAS. WESTERN PENNSYLVANIA CONSERVANCY HAS HELPED ESTABLISH TEN STATE PARKS AND CONSERVED MORE THAN 252,000 ACRES OF NATURAL LANDS.
column88: FALLINGWATER ADMINISTRATION AND EDUCATION PROGRAM: FALLINGWATER IS FRANK LLOYD WRIGHT'S WORLD-FAMOUS MASTERWORK. A HOUSE THAT IS OPERATED AS AN ARCHITECTURAL MUSEUM, FALLINGWATER SYMBOLIZES PEOPLE LIVING IN HARMONY WITH NATURE. FALLINGWATER HOSTS CLOSE TO 167,000 VISITORS, INCLUDING MORE THAN 10,000 STUDENTS, EACH YEAR. FALLINGWATER ALSO PROVIDES CURRICULUM PLANS FOR TEACHERS TO INTEGRATE INTO THEIR CLASSROOMS AND CONDUCTS LECTURES, EXHIBITIONS AND TOURS OF VARIOUS KINDS TO HELP LIFELONG LEARNERS ADVANCE THEIR KNOWLEDGE ABOUT ART, ARCHITECTURE AND NATURE. FALLINGWATER OFFERS ON-SITE WORKSHOPS AND INTERNSHIPS TO FURTHER ENHANCE THE EDUCATIONAL EXPERIENCES AVAILABLE AT THE LOCATION.
column96: COMMUNITY GARDENS & GREENSPACE: THIS PROGRAM IMPLEMENTS HIGH IMPACT GREENING PROJECTS TO PROMOTE ATTRACTIVE AND HEALTHY ENVIRONMENTS AND LIVABLE PLACES. SUPPORTED BY STRATEGIC PARTNERS AND OVER 12,000 VOLUNTEERS, THE PROGRAM ANNUALLY FACILITATES 130 COMMUNITY FLOWER GARDENS, 21 COMMUNITY VEGETABLE GARDENS, AND 1,400 URBAN FLORAL BASKETS AND PLANTERS ALONG CITY STREETS, IMPLEMENTS NATURAL GREEN INFRASTRUCTURE SYSTEMS TO HELP MANAGE STORM WATER DURING WET WEATHER CONDITIONS, AND SINCE 2008, HAS PLANTED 25,300 TREES IN ALLEGHENY COUNTY.

column40: The Partnership reduces substance abuse among adolescents by supporting families and engaging with teens.

column84: The Medicine Abuse Project is a national action campaign that aims to reduce teen initiation of medicine abuse. The campaign provides comprehensive resources for parents and caregivers, law enforcement officials, health care providers, educators and others so that everyone can take a stand and help end this epidemic. The Projects website includes facts about medicine abuse, which includes prescription (Rx) drugs and over-the-counter (OTC) cough medicine. For more information on the medicine abuse project Please see Schedule O.
column88: Above the Influence (ATI) is a national youth program with proven effectiveness that challenges youth, ages 12-17, to think critically about the adverse effects of drug and alcohol use and the potential negative influences surrounding them in their social and media environment. It reaches and connects with teens via public service ads, multiple online and social platforms, and in partnership with community and school-based organizations. Above the Influence is a program of the Partnership for Drug-Free Kids.
column96: The Parent Support Network at the Partnership for Drug-Free Kids offers resources for parents whose teen and young adult children are struggling with drugs and alcohol. It is a very special fusion of head and heart, grounded in the evidence-based principles of motivational interviewing and Community Reinforcement and Family Training (CRAFT). The Parent Support Network helps parents and other caregivers keep open lines of communication and caring with their child, and reduce the damage that is being done to the child and to the family by substance abuse and related behaviors.

column40: Narcolepsy Network is dedicated to improving the lives of people with narcolepsy. Goals include: increasing public awareness, advocating and providing education and resources for people with narcolepsy, promoting and supporting narcolepsy and related research.
column80: The purposes for which the corporation is organized are: educate the public about narcolepsy, support individuals with narcolepsy, promote efficient diagnosis, encourage and promote scientific research for cause, treatments, prevention and cure of narcolepsy, provide for the formation of Chapters, provide funding through solicitation and fund-raising activities for the above-mentioned purposes.
column84: CONFERENCE: Each year Narcolepsy Network (NN) hosts a conference in a different city, which creates a unique gathering for, support, education, awareness building, and networking among people affected by narcolepsy. A selection of workshops, lectures, support forums, energizers and creative activities are some of the offerings at the conference. Graduate students and professionals in health, education, science and government can get a unique perspective on narcolepsy and the effect it has on individuals and families. In 2015, NN hosted the 30th annual conference in Minneapolis, MN. Nearly 450 people with narcolepsy and their supporters attended from all over the world. The conference offered special programming for children and young adults with narcolepsy as well as sessions on research treatment and advocacy. The annual membership meeting was held at the conference and NN presented awards to one researcher. In addition, a new Youth Ambassador program was launched during the 2015 annual conference.
column88: PUBLIC INFORMATION: Information provided for public, academic, medical, and other persons interested in obtaining information about narcolepsy, its causes, symptoms and treatments. Creation and distribution of educational materials and brochures, maintenance of website, interactive forum discussion and social media outreach. NN's Facebook and Twitter pages, with more than 6,000 followers, and an active Facebook support group with nearly 5,000 members continued to bring narcolepsy news and information to people around the world. Fun awareness events continued, including The New York Dream Big Walk, which had more than 145 walkers raise awareness along the Hudson River in New York City. The Third Annual Narcolepsy Bed Race in Virginia also reached more than 60,000 in Southwest Virginia. Narcolepsy Network continued outreach to healthcare providers and educators in 2015, including an initiative to educate medical professionals with two posters that were presented at the SLEEP 2015 meeting, which is attended, by approximately 5,000 sleep professionals. A Youth Ambassador program to support youth with Narcolepsy.
column96: NEWSLETTER, MEMBERSHIP & SCHOLARSHIPS: Our quarterly newsletter, "The Network" is for many people the only source of information about narcolepsy. The newsletter is distributed to the membership as well as many non-member sleep centers and professionals. Each newsletter provides information on diagnosis, effective treatments, resources, updates detailing new narcolepsy research, ideas for coping, personal stories and interviews, industry news, legal and insurance guidance and much more. Approximately 2,000 newsletters are printed quarterly. As part of its mission to provide support to people with narcolepsy, Narcolepsy Network encourages the formation of support groups. There are more than 30 active in-person groups in the U.S. Approximately 30 full and partial membership, and 25 conference scholarships were provided to members in need.

column40: UNH promotes and strengthens the neighborhood based, multi-service approach to improving the lives of New Yorkers in need and the communities in which they live. UNH supports its members through policy development, advocacy and capacity building activities.
column80: UNH promotes and strengthens the neighborhood based, multi-service approach to improving the lives of New Yorkers in need and the communities in which they live. A membership organization rooted in the history and values of the settlement house movement, UNH supports its members through policy development, advocacy and capacity building activities.
column84: During 2015, UNH had the following program accomplishments: POLICY AND ADVOCACY Youth Employment Through its leadership role in the Campaign for Summer Jobs, UNH embarked on the second year of a five year campaign to expand New York Citys Summer Youth Employment Program (SYEP) to 100,000 jobs by 2019. As a result of investments from the City Council, SYEP expanded from serving 47,000 to 50,000 young people. The City Council also invested in a pilot program to provide year-round work experiences for 6,000 youth. After School and Summer CampTo restore funding to after school and summer camp programs which were at risk in the Fiscal Year 2016 City Budget, UNH, as a leader of the Campaign for Children, organized rallies and met with City Council Members and City officials. UNH led a press conference on the steps of City Hall with more than a dozen City Council Members to call for an immediate restoration of cuts to summer camp. As a result of these and other efforts, the City announced on May 29, 2015 that these programs would be restored for the summer.Services for Older AdultsUNH worked with its members and other advocates to urge the Administration to increase funding for NYC Department for the Aging (DFTA)-funded case management services by $3 million to $5.6 million. As a result of this advocacy, the City Council provided $3 million for an initiative in Fiscal Year 2016 to address the waiting lists for case management services. Nonprofit WorkforceUNH made strengthening the nonprofit workforce a priority and is working to improve compensation for the staff that work in human service programs funded by the City. UNH and its partners were successful in advocating for a Cost of Living Adjustment (COLA) and wage floor for this workforce. UNH has also worked with both the City and UNH member agencies to ensure that these needed reforms are implemented effectively. Annual Lobby DaysUNH has expanded its partnership with settlement houses outside of New York City to strengthen its State advocacy. In 2015, UNHs Annual Lobby Days in Albany included partner settlement houses from Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse. These efforts have allowed UNH to have a more effective voice in Albany.Advocacy InstituteUNH offered a three-day training for 27 settlement house front-line staff to teach them about the City and State legislative process. The Advocacy Institute worked with UNH policy staff to customize a practical training designed to educate participants about the budget process and lawmaking. UNH also worked with the Advocacy Institute to map the more than 600 UNH member agency sites. The UNH Policy and Advocacy staff utilized these individual district maps to help elected officials appreciate the range of settlement house services and programs within their community.MEMBER SERVICESEmerging Leaders ProgramIn partnership with Baruch Colleges School of Public Affairs (SPA), UNH offered the Emerging Leaders Program for middle management staff at member agencies. This nine-week course for 24 middle managers focuses on strategic planning, communications, fiscal analysis and planning, quality and outcomes assessments, team building and leadership. UNH initiated The Settlement House Early Childhood Mental Health Collaborative in partnership with the New York Center for Child Development and High Impact Partnering, which is designed to promote the healthy social emotional development and address the mental health needs of young children. The four participating agencies include two UNH settlement houses on the Lower East Side of Manhattan (Grand Street Settlement and Henry Street Settlement), one UNH settlement house in Chelsea, Manhattan (Hudson Guild), and one UNH member agency in Coney Island, Brooklyn (Shorefront YM-YWHA). This project is supported by the New York State Office of Children and Family Services. Talent DevelopmentUNH initiated the Talent Development Initiative to help UNH members develop strategies to identify and cultivate leadership within their organizations. Six members (Union Settlement, Henry Street Settlement, Northern Manhattan Improvement Corporation, BronxWorks, Hartley House and Sunnyside Community Services) participated in this initiative. Each agencys executive leadership team engaged in a series of workshops designed to address their identified goals. UNH also developed a mentoring program matching current and former Executive Directors as mentors for new Executive Directors. A pilot program has been initiated with four mentoring pairs. Emergency PreparednessFollowing a two-year project to improve organizational preparedness for emergencies, UNH launched an Emergency Preparedness webpage which includes materials from workshops conducted during the project and links to other resources on disaster preparedness. In September 2015, UNH convened a forum Community Resiliency and Settlement Houses: Learning from Superstorm Sandy and Preparing for the Future. UNH also produced an issue brief on findings that emerged from its work on emergency preparedness over the last two years. IBM SafetyNet ProjectUNH partnered with IBM to make data collected by UNH members more usable through the implementation of IBMs SafetyNet data management application. The application is currently being implemented with two UNH member agencies Hudson Guild and Stanley M. Isaacs Neighborhood Center. UNH is working to make access to the SafetyNet application available to other UNH members.Responding to Medicaid Redesign With support from The New York Community Trust, UNH began helping its members understand the implications of Medicaid redesign for their programs and make strategic decisions in this challenging environment. This project is working to ensure that the mental health and long-term care programs at settlement houses remain viable in the new Medicaid landscape. Food Access and Community EngagementUNH worked with member organizations to plan healthy food access and utilization projects that are developed in partnership with public-housing community residents. Projects at SCAN New York, Queens Community House and the Jacob A. Riis Neighborhood Settlement have moved into the implementation stage with support from the Laurie M. Tisch Illumination Fund.Through the Older Adults Strengthening Communities Through Food project, UNH is working with older adults in five senior centers to identify healthy food access strategies suited to their respective communities and to develop projects to advance these strategies. Working with staff and participants, the initiative is building the capacity of senior centers to develop, support and sustain these senior-led initiatives. UNH is also leading conversations with others in the field to promote an asset-based approach to programs for older adults.UNH released a report Overcoming the Odds: The Settlement House Advantage which presents findings from a survey of more than 3,000 participant that documented their experience with settlement house programs. The results show that settlement house participants recognize and value the four basic principles that guide the work of the settlement houses: embeddedness, multiple points of entry, reciprocity and community building. Positive outcomesa sense of belonging, a sense of efficacy and a sense of possibilityincreased with the length of time participants had been with the settlement and with the amount of time they spent in programs.

column40: Our mission is to catalyze communities, government, and other institutions to dismantle structural racial inequity and create equitable outcomes for all.
column80: Our mission is to catalyze communities, government, and other institutions to dismantle structural racial inequity and create equitable outcomes for all.
column84: Center for Social Inclusion (CSI) catalyzes community, government, and other institutions to dismantle structural racial inequity and create equitable outcomes for all. Our strategic approach centers on four interlocking strategies: (1) working with community groups and national organizations to develop policy ideas, (2) capacity building through multi-racial coalition building, convenings, leadership development, and trainings, (3) developing tools for communicating about race, and (4) developing and implementing institutional change strategies to operationalize structural racial equity. This past year, CSI began significant work in partnership with the Haas Institute for a Fair and Inclusive Society. The Government Alliance on Race and Equity (GARE) is a project of CSI and leads all work with government, building and sharing effective approaches for building the capacity of local and regional government jurisdictions to advance equity and eliminate institutional and structural racism. Our main program areas and some key 2015 accomplishments are:Government Alliance on Race and Equity (GARE): The Government Alliance on Race and Equity (GARE) is a national network of government working to achieve racial equity and advance opportunities for all. GARE became a core program of CSIs. GARE had previously been associated with the Haas Institute for a Fair and Inclusive Society at University of California, Berkeley, using the Center for Ethical Leadership as a fiscal sponsor. Because of the shared alignment in a structural racism analysis, the move to CSI was ideal. GARE uses a three-prong approach:1)GARE is a membership organization that supports national and regional networks of jurisdictions that are at the forefront of work to achieve racial equity. (Currently, we have 18 cities and counties that are members.)2)GARE offers pathways for new jurisdictions to begin doing racial equity work, including year long learning curricula. (We began intense organizing in California and Minnesota to prepare to launch three year-long learning cohorts.)3)We support and build local and regional collaborations that are broadly inclusive and focused on achieving racial equity, including the provision of tools and resources that work to advance racial equity and create effective and inclusive democracies. (We released a Resource Guide, Racial Equity Tool, and issue papers on public sector jobs and contracting equity.) Energy Democracy: CSI co-convened and co-anchored the formation of the New York Energy Democracy Alliance in New York, a collaborative effort among 15 grassroots and community-based organizations across the state seeking racial and economic equity within the State of New Yorks Reforming the Energy Vision proceedings. Through this work, we have supported community-led policy demands around state energy plans and infrastructure development, and pushed for the dedication of 40% (winning 30%) of clean energy funds to go to low-income, communities of color, and environmental justice communities. Additionally, CSI has supported and facilitated a series of national strategy sessions with grassroots leaders and environmental advocates to address policy strategies that will build towards Energy Democracy. Transportation Equity: CSI worked in two areas: (1) identifying clear equity policy demands, including around performance measures and community indicators on transportation decision-making, developed to create greater transparency, accountability, and participatory processes at the federal, state, and local level, and (2) deep work across community and government to support transit equity campaigns and institutional practice in key localities and regions. As a member of the national Transportation for America (T4A) Coalition and as a steering committee member of the now independent Equity Caucus, CSI incorporates a racially inclusive policy lens into federal transportation policy by identifying and supporting the transit priorities and concerns of communities of color, and by connecting them to national policy discussions. CSI also supports the Caucus by convening the Data and Performance Measures policy subcommittee. Locally, CSI led several sessions in both Detroit and Seattle. Additionally, CSI convened a group of local and national advocates to discuss a framework for performance management. Food and Health Equity: CSI is working with local leaders to do an assessment of the leadership of Black farmers in the South, identifying the opportunities and challenges towards developing out racially equitable and viable food hubs that can connect families and communities to healthy and affordable foods. In New York City, CSI has convened grassroots leaders seeking to develop out a micro-food hub as a model for urban agricultural innovation and entrepreneurship that will support people of color-owned food enterprises, community agriculture, and most of all build wealth through food systems to be a solution to displacement and inequity. Nationally, CSI participates in the Good Food For All Collaborative and the Health, Environment, Agriculture and Labor (HEAL) Alliance. In addition to CSIs work on food equity, CSI expanded the program area to include health equity with a focus on First Food/breastfeeding. We also released Removing Barriers to Breastfeedingan action oriented structural race analysis of the First Food system. We also announced CSIs First Food cohort will take place before the end of 2016 as well, and led a dozen workshops and presentations relating to First Food/breastfeeding research and the structural race analysis. Leaders: CSI continued work to build 21st century leadership for racial equity across grassroots, grasstops, government and in other institutions, including philanthropy. Over the course of the year, CSI facilitated over two dozen workshops with various sectors. CSI also successfully designed and executed three full-day workshop sessions in Detroit with the Detroit Equity Action Lab, CSIs Detroit cohort. CSI worked to set the groundwork to launch a community cohort focused on energy, infrastructure and the environment in the Puget Sound region. In the Fall, CSI began work to support several Annie E. Casey Foundation grantee sites through racial equity technical assistance.Race Communications: CSI produced and released a reportour second major publication on Race CommunicationsLets Talk about Race: How Racially Explicit Messaging Can Advance Equity, and strengthened relationships with organizations through dissemination of the results. CSI has established relationships with both national and local organizations across the nation, like Arkansas Public Policy Panel, Public Works, Restaurant Opportunity Center, and Youth Jobs Coalitions. Communications: In terms of number of earned media placements, 2015 is our second highest performing year (2013 had the highest in terms of unique placements and media impressions). This performance is largely due to media work by Deepa Iyer, Simran Noor, Anthony Giancatarino, and Glenn Harris. Highlights include placements on MSNBCs Melissa Harris-Perry, The Guardian-US, Grist Magazine, The Hill, Yes! Magazine, and several local and regional newspapers across the country. We had moderate success with our digital media tools, experiencing steady growth on Facebook, Twitter, and our newsletterthough we are below average in percent increase compared to organizations like Human Rights Campaign, Jobs with Justice, and other rights-based organizations based on M+Rs 2015 benchmarks report on the non-profit industry. However, our statistics are on par with our sister organizations like Advancement Project, Movement Strategy Center, and Opportunity Agenda. Lastly, Communications made significant headway for the organizational rebrand which is occurring in 2016.Multiracial Solidarity: As the American racial landscape changes, activists, organizers, and thought leaders are engaging in dialogues and practicing solidarity across various movements. CSIs Senior Fellow Deepa Iyer has been developing thought pieces and participating in conversations around advancing racial justice and equity. Deepa convened 8 community conversations using her book, We Too Sing America: South Asian, Arab, Muslim and Sikh Immigrants Shape Our Multiracial Future (The New Press), wrote five opinion editorials in outlets, including The Guardian, The Nation, and Colorlines, and provided radio interviews for over 10 local programs on issues ranging from the post 9/11 environment to solidarity across communities of color. Deepa also participated in several Solidarity Summits convened by the Open Society Foundations (OSF), the Proteus Fund, and the Ford Foundation.

column40: LIVEWELL COLORADO'S MISSION IS TO PREVENT AND REDUCE OBESITY.
column80: LIVEWELL COLORADO IS A STATEWIDE NON-PROFIT ORGANIZATION COMMITTED TO PREVENTING AND REDUCING OBESITY IN COLORADO BY PROMOTING HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING. SEE SCHEDULE O FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.IN ADDITION TO EDUCATING AND SUPPORTING PEOPLE TO MAKE HEALTHY CHOICES, LIVEWELL COLORADO FOCUSES ON POLICY, ENVIRONMENTAL AND LIFESTYLE CHANGES THAT REMOVE BARRIERS AND INCREASE ACCESS TO HEALTHY BEHAVIORS. WORKING IN PARTNERSHIP WITH OBESITY PREVENTION INITIATIVES ACROSS THE STATE, LIVEWELL COLORADO AIMS TO PROVIDE EVERY COLORADAN WITH ACCESS TO HEALTHY FOODS AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR PHYSICAL ACTIVITY TO MAKE COLORADO THE HEALTHIEST STATE IN THE NATION.
column84: LOCAL INITIATIVES: COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIPS- LIVEWELL COLORADO'S (LWC) COMMUNITY PARTNERSHIP PROGRAM FUNDS COMMUNITY COALITIONS WORKING ON HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING STRATEGIES AT THE LOCAL LEVEL. AWARDED $1.6 MILLION IN FUNDING TO 16 COMMUNITIES ACROSS THE STATE THAT REPRESENT LOW SOCIO-ECONOMIC AREAS WITH HIGHER OBESITY RATES; PROVIDED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR SHARED KNOWLEDGE AND COLLABORATIONS TO INCREASE SUSTAINABILITY INCLUDING COMMUNITY VISITS, PHONE CONSULTATIONS, WEBINARS, ROUNDTABLE DISCUSSIONS, TRAININGS AND MEETINGS THAT PROMOTE INCREASED KNOWLEDGE OF HEALTHY FOOD, ACTIVE COMMUNITY ENVIRONMENTS, AND GRASSROOTS ADVOCACY. SEE SCHEDULE O FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.SUPPORTED TARGETED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE RELATED TO COMMUNITY ORGANIZING AND ENGAGING/EMPOWERING THE TARGET POPULATION.COLLABORATED WITH LOCAL PARTNERS AND DISTRIBUTED $132K IN PARTNER GRANTS TO INCREASE YOUTH PARTICIPATION IN LOCAL RECREATION CENTERS BY CONNECTING YOUTH TO RECREATION CENTER PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT AND BUILT ENVIRONMENT IMPROVEMENTS. THE YOUTH-DRIVEN HEALTHY RECREATION CENTERS COLLECTIVE GRANT, WHICH WAS IMPLEMENTED IN DENVER'S SWANSEA, ST. CHARLES AND STAPLETON RECREATION CENTERS, HELPED TURN REC CENTERS INTO PLACES WHERE YOUTH CHOOSE TO SPEND TIME AND LEARN NEW SKILLS FOR HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING. IN A SURVEY, 92 PERCENT OF PARTICIPATING YOUTH REPORTED EATING MORE FRUITS AND VEGETABLES, 85 PERCENT SAID THEY HAD CUT BACK ON ELECTRONIC DEVICES IN FAVOR OF MORE PHYSICAL ACTIVITY, AND 70 PERCENT STARTED COOKING MEALS WITH THEIR FAMILIES. THIS PARTNERSHIP GRANT WAS AN EIGHTEEN-MONTH COLLABORATION BETWEEN LIVEWELL AND SEVEN PARTNER ORGANIZATIONS IN THE METRO AREA. LIVEWELL @SCHOOL FOOD INITIATIVE- INVESTED OVER $1.06 MILLION IN PROGRAMS TO TRANSITION SCHOOL DISTRICT KITCHEN OPERATIONS TO OFFER FRESHLY PREPARED STUDENT MEALS. CONDUCTED SCHOOL MEAL ASSESSMENTS WITH RECOMMENDATIONS FOR SCHOOL DISTRICTS, PRESENTED CULINARY WORKSHOPS TO TEACH FUNDAMENTALS OF SCRATCH COOKING, AND DEDICATED A TEAM OF ON-SITE CHEF CONSULTANTS TO PARTNER WITH DISTRICTS THROUGHOUT THE SCHOOL YEAR IN CREATING AND IMPLEMENTING SUSTAINABLE CULINARY ACTION PLANS TO IMPROVE STUDENT MEALS. IMPLEMENTED PROGRAM EVALUATION TOOLS TO ASSESS SUSTAINABLE CHANGES. TRANSFORMED AND REFINED THE SCHOOL FOOD INITIATIVE TO BETTER ALIGN WITH SCHOOL SCHEDULES AND THE SCHOOL FOOD ENVIRONMENT, INCLUDING A COMPLETE FACELIFT OF THE MATERIALS, PROCESSES AND PROFESSIONAL TEAM. AN INAUGURAL SUSTAINABILITY WORKSHOP WAS INTRODUCED TO HELP SCHOOL DISTRICTS TO EXTEND THE YEAR-ONE HANDS-ON COACHING AND TRAINING FOR MULTIPLE YEARS. HEAL CITIES & TOWNS CAMPAIGN - CONTINUED EXPANDING THE LIVEWELL COLORADO HEAL CITIES AND TOWNS CAMPAIGN IN PARTNERSHIP WITH THE COLORADO MUNICIPAL LEAGUE TO ENCOURAGE MUNICIPALITIES TO PASS AND IMPLEMENT LOCAL HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING RELATED POLICIES. GREW TO 42 PARTICIPATING MUNICIPALITIES DURING THE YEAR, INCLUDING CARBONDALE, CENTENNIAL, GLENWOOD SPRINGS, GREELEY, KIOWA, MONTROSE, RIFLE AND SAGUACHE. HOSTED THE THIRD ANNUAL HEAL SUMMIT, WHICH BROUGHT TOGETHER MUNICIPAL AND COMMUNITY LEADERS TO LEARN AND SHARE BEST POLICY AND ENVIRONMENTAL PRACTICES TO CREATE HEALTHIER CITIES AND TOWNS. THE EVENT DREW MORE THAN 100 ATTENDEES.
column88: COMMUNICATIONS: LIVEWELL COLORADO'S COMMUNICATIONS AND MARKETING STRATEGY INCLUDED COMMUNITY-BASED SOCIAL MARKETING AND COMMUNICATIONS CAMPAIGNS WHICH CONSISTED OF MASS MEDIA, MEDIA RELATIONS, SOCIAL MEDIA, COMMUNITY EVENTS, AND INTERVENTIONS AIMED TO INCREASE HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING (HEAL) BEHAVIORS. SEE SCHEDULE O FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.ENGAGED OVER 65,000 FACEBOOK FRIENDS AND 5,000 TWITTER FOLLOWERS TO DATE WHO SHARE ONLINE HEALTHY EATING AND ACTIVE LIVING (HEAL) INFORMATION WITH THEIR NETWORKS THROUGH SOCIAL MEDIA. IN 2015, LIVEWELL EVOLVED TO A NEW COMMUNICATIONS APPROACH FOCUSED ON BUILDING AND MOBILIZING CHAMPIONS FOR HEALTH, RAISING AWARENESS ABOUT BARRIERS TO HEALTHY AND AFFORDABLE FOOD AND PHYSICAL ACTIVITY, AND ENCOURAGING ACTIONS THAT ADVANCE THE OPPORTUNITY FOR MORE COLORADANS TO HAVE ACCESS TO HEALTHY LIVING. COMMUNICATIONS ACTIVITIES ALSO SUPPORTED THE ORGANIZATIONAL INFRASTRUCTURE NEEDED TO SHARE INFORMATION, PROMOTE THE WORK OF OUR COMMUNITY AND STATE PARTNERS, AND MOBILIZE THE NETWORK OF ADVOCATES AND CHAMPIONS AND KEEP THEM ENGAGED.
column96: POLICY AND ADVOCACY: HOSTED SIXTH ANNUAL DAY AT THE CAPITOL IN FEBRUARY, INCLUDING A HEALTHY MEET-AND-GREET BREAKFAST AND A PANEL OF POLICYMAKERS WHO INFLUENCE HEAL POLICY IN A VARIETY OF WAYS. CONTINUED TO SUPPORT THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE COLORADO FOOD POLICY NETWORK (COFPN) AND ITS LEADERSHIP COUNCIL IN PARTNERSHIP WITH CSU EXTENSION. THE COFPN BROUGHT TOGETHER THE 18 LOCAL FOOD POLICY COUNCILS FROM ACROSS THE STATE TO PROMOTE HEALTHY, COMMUNITY-BASED, ECONOMICALLY VIABLE FOOD SYSTEMS IN COLORADO THAT ENSURE ALL RESIDENTS HAVE ACCESS TO AFFORDABLE, NUTRITIOUS FOOD. SEE SCHEDULE O FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.CORE AREAS OF FOCUS WERE BUILDING THE CAPACITY OF LOCAL FOOD SYSTEMS COALITIONS TO EFFECT POLICY CHANGE AND ADVANCING STATE LEVEL POLICIES, INVESTMENTS AND STRATEGIES THROUGH A COLLECTIVE APPROACH. WORKED WITH A COALITION OF PARTNERS TO ADVOCATE FOR DEDICATED FUNDING FOR SAFE ROUTES TO SCHOOL INFRASTRUCTURE AND EDUCATION, FOR WHICH $2.5 MILLION WAS COMMITTED ANNUALLY. SUCCESSFULLY ENSURED THE DEFEAT OF A PROPOSAL TO REPEAL THE STATE SODA TAX. WEIGHED IN ON FEDERAL POLICY ISSUES INCLUDING CHILD NUTRITION REAUTHORIZATION AND A FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION PROPOSAL TO LIST SUGAR ON FOOD NUTRITION LABELS. LAUNCHED A NEW PILOT PROJECT (PASS PROJECT: POLICY ASSISTANCE, STRATEGY SUPPORT) TO SUPPORT POLICY CHANGES IN THE COMMUNITIES WHERE LIVEWELL HAS EXISTING PARTNERS. THE PROJECT IS TO PROVIDED TARGETED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO ASSIST IN STRATEGIZING, PASSING, AND IMPLEMENTING COMMUNITY-BASED, LOCAL-LEVEL HEAL POLICY INITIATIVES. CREATED AN INAUGURAL LIVEWELL PUBLIC POLICY COMMITTEE (WHICH INCLUDED DIVERSE REPRESENTATION FROM URBAN AND RURAL COLORADO) TO ADVANCE EFFORTS THAT WILL LEVERAGE LOCAL-LEVEL PARTNERS TO INFORM AND ADVOCATE ON BEHALF OF A SHARED, STATEWIDE POLICY PLATFORM. CONVENED A BROAD AND DIVERSE GROUP OF PARTNERS TO APPLY FOR A FEDERAL GRANT FROM THE UNITED STATES DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE WHICH WILL GIVE LOW-INCOME FAMILIES THE ABILITY TO PURCHASE MORE COLORADO-GROWN FRESH FRUITS AND VEGETABLES AT FARMERS MARKETS THROUGHOUT THE STATE.

column80: THE ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH STRATEGY CENTER PROMOTES HUMAN HEALTH AND SAFER CHEMICALS IN A SUSTAINABLE ECONOMY. WE WORK FOR HEALTHY PEOPLE WHO THRIVE IN A HEALTHY ECONOMY BY REDUCING EXPOSURE TO TOXIC CHEMICALS IN OUR HOMES AND PROMOTING PRODUCTS THAT ARE SAFE FOR PEOPLE AND THE PLANET. IN STATE AND NATIONAL CAMPAIGNS, WE USE RESEARCH AND EDUCATION TO REFORM POLICIES, CHANGE THE MARKETPLACE, AND ADVANCE SCIENCE-BASED SOLUTIONS THAT ARE SOCIALLY JUST. TO CARRY OUT ITS MISSION, THE STRATEGY CENTER FOCUSES WORK IN TWO MAJOR PROGRAM AREAS. THE ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH PROGRAM'S ULTIMATE GOAL IS TO PREVENT CANCER, DISABILITIES, AND OTHER ENVIRONMENTAL DISEASES. THE SUSTAINABLE ECONOMY PROGRAM AIMS TO CREATE AND RETAIN GOOD PAYING JOBS MAKING SAFER SUSTAINABLE PRODUCTS.
column84: ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH PROGRAM:IN 2015, WE EDUCATED THE PUBLIC ABOUT THE HEALTH HAZARDS ASSOCIATED WITH TOXIC CHEMICALS KNOWN AS PHTHALATES, AND CONVINCED THE STATE OF MAINE TO REQUIRE MANUFACTURERS TO REPORT TOXIC PHTHALATE IN HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS SOLD THROUGHOUT THE STATE. WE HELPED TO PASS A BILL LAST YEAR TO IMPROVE TESTING AND TREATMENT OF THE WELL WATER THAT NEARLY HALF OF ALL MAINERS DRINK. ONE IN EIGHT MAINE WELLS CONTAINS ARSENIC ABOVE SAFE LEVELS. ARSENIC IS LINKED TO SKIN, BLADDER, AND LUNG CANCERS, AND LEARNING. WE INITIATED AN EDUCATION AND ORGANIZING CAMPAIGN TO PROMOTE SAFE DRINKING WATER THROUGHOUT THE STATE. WE RECRUITED AND TRAINED FIVE COLLEGE-LEVEL INTERNS TO CONDUCT RESEARCH ON CRITICAL ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH ISSUES AND CONDUCT GRASSROOTS EDUCATION AND ORGANIZING ACTIVITIES TO INCREASE PUBLIC AWARENESS AND ENGAGEMENT ADDRESSING THE LINK BETWEEN HUMAN HEALTH AND TOXIC CHEMICALS THROUGHOUT THE STATE OF MAINE. NATIONALLY, WE PROVIDED LEADERSHIP AND ASSISTANCE TO SAFER CHEMICALS HEALTHY FAMILIES, THE LEADING COALITION WORKING TO REFORM CURRENT NATIONAL CHEMICAL POLICY. WE ADVISED ON POLICY DEVELOPMENT, CAMPAIGN STRATEGY AND TACTICS TO THE COALITION. WE ALSO HELPED TO COORDINATE STATE AND NATIONAL CHEMICAL POLICY REFORM IN A CONSULTING ROLE TO THE SAFER STATES COALITION. IN THE MARKETPLACE, WE HAD VICTORIES IN THE NATIONAL MIND THE STORE CAMPAIGN TO ENCOURAGE RETAILERS TO ELIMINATE TOXIC CHEMICALS FROM THE PRODUCTS THEY SELL. EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR MIKE BELLIVEAU LED NEGOTIATIONS THAT CONVINCED THE WORLD'S LARGEST HOME-IMPROVEMENT RETAIL CHAIN, THE HOME DEPOT, TO STOP SEEING VINYL FLOORING MADE WITH PHTHALATES, HORMONE-DISRUPTING TOXIC CHEMICALS. OTHER MAJOR RETAILERS FOLLOWED THEIR LEAD. ALSO THIS YEAR, FOUR MAJOR FURNITURE RETAILERS HAVE PLEDGED TO ELIMINATE UNNECESSARY TOXIC FLAME RETARDANT CHEMICALS FROM THE FURNITURE IN THEIR STORES.
column88: SUSTAINABLE ECONOMY PROGRAM: IN 2015, WE CONTINUED TO PROMOTE THE MANUFACTURE OF SAFER CHEMICALS MADE FROM RENEWABLE, SUSTAINABLE, BIOBASED MATERIALS FROM FOREST, FARM, AND SEA, TO REPLACE TOXIC CHEMICALS DERIVED FROM PETROLEUM. WE CONNECTED RESEARCHERS AND DEVELOPERS WITH POTENTIAL INVESTORS, AND ANALYZED THE SIGNIFICANT MARKET OPPORTUNITIES FOR TO BRING GOOD-PAYING, SUSTAINABLE, GREEN JOBS TO MAINE'S ECONOMY. OUR EFFORTS CONTINUED TO DEVELOP AN OVERALL LONG-TERM ROADMAP FOR INVESTMENT IN THE EMERGING AND GROWING BIOBASED BUSINESS SECTOR IN MAINE. WE STAFF THE TRADE ASSOCIATION, BIOBASED MAINE, WHICH PROMOTES INNOVATIVE, NEW BIOBASED INDUSTRIES AND PRODUCTS.
