column84: 1) CLICC In 2014, Connecticut Appleseed began drawing on the $294,000 Second Chance Act grant from the U.S. Department of Justice for the Centers Connecting through Literacy Incarcerated Parents, Children and Caregivers program (CLICC). The two-year grant is intended to bring Appleseeds CLICC program to two of Connecticuts state prisons in collaboration with the Connecticut Department of Corrections. In 2015 CLICC staff received an extension to three years, while also expanding CLICC from two of Connecticuts state prisons to four collaborating with the Connecticut Department of Corrections to include Cybulski and Enfield Correctional Institutions. CLICCs program is Adult Mentoring and Transitional Services for Successful Reentry Program: Mentoring of Adult Offenders: Promoting Successful Reentry through Responsible Father / Motherhood". The CLICC program mitigates two pressing challenges: 1) below-average literacy rates of incarcerated parents and their children, and 2) strained, often destructive relationships among families which include an incarcerated parent. Reinforcing the literacy skills of re-entering inmates and their children will help to ease their transition, help the family move forward more cohesively and better equip former inmates to enter the workforce.Pairs of CLICC mentors and children have been matched since the program began in Bridgeport, New Haven, Norwalk, Trumbull and West Haven. The families served by CLICC mentors in 2015 included roughly 20 parents and 30 children, for a total of 50 participants. Pro bono services estimated at 450 hours, valued at $33,750.Cash expenses for program = $136,284.

column80: Since 1980, Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD) has been the premier voice for victims and survivors of drunk and drugged driving. It is a voice that has passionately advocated for change at the state and national levels; it is a voice that has compassionately consoled the inconsolable when tragedy strikes; and it is a voice that educates parents and communities about how to keep youth safe from the dangers of underage drinking. In 2015, MADD celebrated its 35th anniversary by adding drugged driving back to its mission statement (the original mission statement in 1980 also included drugged driving) and unveiling the organizations first ever tagline "No More Victims". These are just two key milestones in an impactful and eventful year. Advocate We are frustrated we arent saving enough lives fast enough. column84: INTERNATIONAL DONOR ADVISED GIVING - The International Donor Advised Giving (IDAG) program at United Way Worldwide continues to drive global philanthropic impact in conjunctions with international United Ways and other global non-governmental organizations (NGOs). In 2015, we: 1) Helped 69 corporations, foundations, and individual connect with and fund international projects in 83 countries; 2) Processed a total of 594 grants which funded multiple international education, income, and health programs; 3) Facilitated $444,815 to aid in the recovery efforts related to disasters in India, Nepal, and the Philippines.
column88: U.S. NETWORK - Creates opportunity for all Americans to succeed in life through our work in Education, Income, and Health. We provide support and leadership to the nearly 1,200 community-based United Ways across the United States by leveraging strategic partnerships that drive impact in our communities and advocate for government policies in support of our mission. In 2015, we focused on: 1) Strengthening the organizational capacity of United Ways to meet local and national fundraising goals to fuel community impact in Education, Income, and Health; 2) Contributing expertise and support to UNITED WAYS AROUND several national issues including tax incentives, Earned Income Tax Credit, youth employment, children's health insurance programs; and 3) Creating or enhancing cross-sector partnerships that bring local United Ways together with corporate partners, labor, government, nonprofits, foundations, 2-1-1-, content experts and others to ensure that member United Ways can execute on the mission both individually and collectively as a network.
column96: IMPACT, STRATEGY and INNOVATION--The Impact, Strategy and Innovation team at United Way Worldwide provides strategic and tactical support to drive priority impact work globally and accelerate solutions by leveraging innovation, research, and volunteerism. It develops and advances the network-wide strategy, manages national and global strategic initiatives, and provides capacity to develop and scale innovation across the United Way network. In 2015, UWW partnered with hundreds of United Ways and partners across sectors to advance worldwide signature impact initiatives: childhood success, youth success, economic mobility, and access to health.

column40: THE COMMUNITY FOUNDATION MANAGES OVER 600 CHARITABLE FUNDS ESTABLISHED TO STRENGTHEN ITS COMMUNITIES BY PROVIDING SUPPORT TO A BROAD RANGE OF COMMUNITY NEEDS, NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS, AND EDUCATIONAL OPPORTUNITIES.
column80: The Community Foundation of Greater Greensboro is dedicated to strengthening the community for present and future generations. The Community Foundation promotes philanthropy, builds and maintains a permanent collection of endowment funds and serves as a trustworthy partner and leader in shaping effective responses to community issues and opportunities.
column84: Donor Advised: The Community Foundation manages 290 donor-advised and scholarship funds which enable residents of Greater Greensboro to achieve their individual charitable goals. During 2015, more than 1800 grants were disbursed in support of faith based, health & human service, educational and other community service organizations.
column88: Field of Interest: The Community Foundation manages endowment and unrestricted grant funds which are used to strengthen its communities for present and future generations. Focus areas for 2015 were to promote economic development through community initiatives, including the development of a performing arts center, establishing workforce initiatives to align education and training with business needs, and, through the generous bequest from a long-term resident, the construction of a public park. In addition, area residents have created permanent funds to support specific areas of interest, including issues concerning our community's women and families, tuition assistance for eligible high school graduates, and shaping our community's identity through the use of art in public areas. These funds make grants while also conducting active endowment building activities.
column96: Organizational funds: Area residents have created funds to support specific nonprofit organizations. In addition, The Community Foundation manages the endowment funds of local nonprofit organizations; accordingly the Foundation recognizes a liability to the nonprofit and adjusts this liability for related contributions, earnings, grants and expenses. In 2015, $2.6 million was returned to these organizations.

column84: DURING THE LAST YEAR, RESOURCES LEGACY FUND (RLF) CARRIED OUT PROGRAMS AND AWARDED GRANTS TO SUPPORT ACTIVITIES THAT WORK TO IMPROVE ENVIRONMENTAL SUSTAINABILITY IN WESTERN NORTH AMERICA AS WELL AS IN OCEANS AND FISHERIES WORLDWIDE. SELECT RLF ACCOMPLISHMENTS DURING 2015 INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING:RLF COORDINATED AND SUPPORTED THE EARLY 2015 COMPLETION OF A PUBLIC PROCESS FOR DEVELOPING A PLAN FOR ENSURING THE LONG-TERM SUSTAINABILITY OF CALIFORNIA'S STATE PARKS. THE PLAN RESULTED FROM MORE THAN 18 MONTHS OF RESEARCH, OUTREACH, AND COORDINATION BETWEEN A PUBLICLY APPOINTED COMMISSION, KEY STATE AGENCIES, AND THE ADMINISTRATION OF THE GOVERNOR OF CALIFORNIA. IT DETAILED A FUNDAMENTAL TRANSFORMATION OF THE STATE'S PARK SYSTEM, AND RECOMMENDED MAJOR CHANGES TO MODERNIZE THE SYSTEM, ENGAGE PARTNERS, AND EXPAND ACCESS. AFTER THE PLAN'S COMPLETION, RLF CONTINUED TO WORK WITH THE CALIFORNIA DEPARTMENT OF PARKS AND RECREATION TO IMPLEMENT THE RECOMMENDATIONS THROUGH THE DEPARTMENT'S TRANSFORMATION INITIATIVE.RLF LAUNCHED THE CALIFORNIA DROUGHT ACTION INITIATIVE-COMPRISING A RANGE OF TARGETED OUTREACH AND EDUCATION EFFORTS-WITH THE AIM USING DROUGHT-AMPLIFIED PUBLIC AND DECISION-MAKER ATTENTION TO ADVANCE CHANGES IN HOW THE STATE MANAGES ITS WATER. THIS INCLUDED SUPPORTING EFFORTS TO (1) DRIVE CREATION OF A ROBUST, STATEWIDE WATER MARKET BY ESTABLISHING A COMPREHENSIVE AND ACCESSIBLE WATER DATA SYSTEM; (2) SECURE SUSTAINABLE FUNDING FOR DEVELOPMENT OF NEW LOCAL WATER SOURCES SUCH AS CAPTURED STORMWATER AND RECYCLED WASTEWATER; AND (3) ENSURE THAT ALL CALIFORNIA COMMUNITIES HAVE ADEQUATE, SUSTAINABLE, AND AFFORDABLE SUPPLIES OF SAFE DRINKING WATER. TO PROMOTE SUSTAINABLE FISHERIES WORLDWIDE, RLF PROVIDED SUPPORT TO OVERCOME FINANCIAL AND TECHNICAL OBSTACLES TO FISHERY AND STAKEHOLDER PARTICIPATION IN THE MARINE STEWARDSHIP COUNCIL (MSC) FISHERY CERTIFICATION PROGRAM. FOR EXAMPLE, RLF GRANTS SUPPORTED MULTI-FISHERY PRE-ASSESSMENTS IN FRANCE, SPAIN, ICELAND, AND JAMAICA; DESIGN OF FISHERY IMPROVEMENT PROJECTS FOR SEVEN SMALL-SCALE FISHERIES IN BRAZIL; AND TESTING OF A CAPACITY BUILDING TOOLKIT FOR DEVELOPING INTERNATIONAL STAKEHOLDERS SEEKING TO ENGAGE IN FISHERY IMPROVEMENT PROJECTS ALIGNED WITH THE MSC STANDARD. IN ADDITION, TO ENABLE FISHERIES MANAGED BY THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA TO MEET GLOBAL STANDARDS FOR MANAGEMENT AND SUSTAINABILITY, RLF SUPPORTED THE TESTING OF TOOLS FOR ANALYZING THE STATUS AND PERFORMANCE OF CALIFORNIA FISHERIES; DEVELOPMENT OF MORE EFFECTIVE APPROACHES TO STAKEHOLDER ENGAGEMENT; AND SCOPING AN ASSESSMENT OF STATE FISHERIES DATA COLLECTION, MANAGEMENT, AND ANALYSIS PROGRAMS.RLF WORKED WITH THE SAN FRANCISCO BAYLANDS STEERING COMMITTEE, MANAGING A PUBLIC EDUCATION CAMPAIGN, OUR BAY ON THE BRINK, TO INFORM THE PUBLIC ABOUT SIGNIFICANT ENVIRONMENTAL THREATS TO THE SAN FRANCISCO BAY AND POTENTIAL SOLUTIONS. USING TARGETED DIGITAL MEDIA, EARNED MEDIA, BILLBOARDS, AND MAIL, THE OUTREACH CAMPAIGN INCREASED UNDERSTANDING OF FLOOD AND SEA LEVEL RISE IMPACTS AS WELL AS THREATS TO WILDLIFE AND COMMUNITIES.IN NORTHWEST MEXICO, RLF SUPPORTED THE PROTECTION OF 14,033 STRATEGICALLY TARGETED ACRES, AS WELL AS GRANTEE ACTIVITIES THAT IMPLEMENTED COMPLEMENTARY ORGANIZATIONAL CAPACITY, COMMUNICATION, SCIENCE, AND OTHER STRATEGIES TO ADVANCE CONSERVATION IN THE REGION.

column40: THE NATURAL RESOURCES COUNCIL OF MAINE IS A NONPROFIT MEMBERSHIP ORGANIZATION PROTECTING, RESTORING, AND CONSERVING MAINE'S ENVIRONMENT, NOW AND FOR FUTURE GENERATIONS.
column80: Founded in 1959 by Maine citizens, the Natural Resources Council of Maine (NRCM) is the state's leading non-profit environmental organization. Our mission is to protect, restore and conserve Maine's environment, now and for future generations. We use science, outreach, and advocacy to educate and engage our members, supporters, policy makers and the public about the most pressing environmental issues facing Maine. Our overarching goal is to inspire people to become better stewards of Maine's natural resources. NRCM focuses on four program areas: 1. Climate and Clean Energy; 2. Healthy Waters; 3. Forests and Wildlife; and, 4. Sustainable Maine.
column84: Communications NRCM communicates with our members, supporters, policy makers, and the public using email updates and calls to action, community meetings and events, single issue reports, consumer guides (e.g., Bright Ideas: Tips for Home Energy Savings pamphlet), direct mail, radio, and our website, www.nrcm.org. These tools support our mission and advance our work in each of our issue areas. NRCM distributes our printed newsletter, Maine Environment, to over 7,500 people three times per year, featuring updates on current environmental issues, recent activities, upcoming events, and a special column by NRCM Executive Director Dr. Lisa Pohlmann. In 2015, we published a recap of our legislative achievements in a special edition of the newsletter entitled Report Card for Maine's Environment, and distributed 15,000 copies statewide. We also continued the Explore Maine edition of the newsletter as a special insert in our spring issue. For the second year in a row, Explore Maine encouraged our members and supporters to enjoy Maine through books written by NRCM members, art and photography exhibits showcasing the beauty of Maine, and visits to Maine sporting camps that offer discounts to NRCM members. The NRCM website, www.nrcm.org, is a critical tool that informs our members and supporters, the public, and policy makers about our work. Our most recent data analysis reveals that, between July 1, 2015-June 30, 2016, our website received 509,765 total visits, representing 124,475 unique visitors. On average our website served 1,393 visitors per day. Social media is another key way we engage our constituents. Facebook is our most popular social media tool, with 6,279 people who "like" NRCM's Facebook page. This level of interest surpasses the national benchmark of 355 fans per 1,000 supporters, which for an organization of our size means we can expect about 5,680 page "likes". Our supporters are also active readers of our monthly electronic newsletter. The average open rate for this NRCM communication is 19.2% (surpassing the national average of 17%). More than 15,500 members and supporters currently receive this monthly e-newsletter. NRCM also uses our informative blog posts to educate and engage people in our issues, encourage them to get outside and enjoy Maine's natural beauty, and inspire appreciation for Maine's wildlife and quality of life. In 2015 we added four new blogs: Spotlight on Sustainability in Maine, dedicated to sharing information about the people, places, and initiatives making a positive difference for our environment; Engaging Maine Middle School Students in the Nature of Maine which focuses on eight different middle school projects funded by NRCM with seed grants; Consequences and Hope in the Environmental Century by Dr. Stephen Mulkey, former NRCM board member and educator, is a scholarly analysis of ecological changes driven by climate change; and, Quest for Protection: The Headwaters of Maine's North Woods, which offers a four season look at the headwaters of five major rivers in the North Woods. In 2015, NRCM continued the unique partnership we began in 2013 with a popular local radio station to offer Maine Green Minute, which are one-minute public service announcements broadcast four times daily about steps people can take to protect the environment, conserve natural resources, and live in a more sustainable way. Sample topics in 2015 included: facts about the wasting of millions of trees to print junk mail and how to stop getting junk mail at your home; chemical-free household cleaners and skin-care products; alternatives to foam plates and cups; plants that attract hummingbirds and help bees thrive; and tips for saving on home energy costs.
column88: Environmental advocacy, NRCM is Maine's top environmental watchdog. We represent environmental interests at the Maine Legislature, and before state agencies responsible for managing our state's natural resources. These include the Department of Environmental Protection, the Land Use Planning Commission, the Department of Agriculture, Conservation, and Forestry, and the Public Utilities Commission. Performing within our 501(c)(3) allowable lobbying limits, NRCM lobbyists monitor issues related to our programs as well as emerging environmental issues. We use grassroots and direct lobbying to generate public and policymaker support for strong, science-based environmental protections. We also mobilize Maine people to defend Maine's environmental policies and programs from powerful special interests seeking weaker regulations or unsustainable use of Maine's natural resources. Our staff attend legislative work sessions (to observe and to serve as a resource for legislators), testify at public hearings, and serve on stakeholder groups. We provide an environmental perspective to policy discussions, offer analysis of the long-term impacts of policy decisions, and in many cases help to balance the proposals of extractive industries, which may focus solely on short-term economic gain. NRCM's activities help foster a clear understanding by policymakers, state officials, and the public that strong environmental safeguards and a sustainable Maine economy go hand-in-hand. Our staff also research, produce, and make publicly available on our website fact sheets about the issues we are working on, testimony given before the Maine Legislature, comments we provide to state agencies, and special publications and reports on key environmental issues and bills being considered by the Legislature. We use these tools to further inform and engage a broad range of people with current environmental issues and steps they can take to help shape environmental policy in the state.
column96: Climate & Clean Energy, Climate change is the most serious environmental threat of our time and requires action at all levels. NRCM's leadership and guidance has helped Maine make progress to reduce our dependence on fossil fuels, cut carbon pollution, and address climate change. Policy advocacy, civic engagement, and public outreach are at the heart of NRCM's strategies to address climate change and advance clean energy solutions. We promote funding increases for energy efficiency programs, rally support for more renewable power such as solar, and support action at the local, state, and federal levels to address climate change. Our work is critical to reducing health and environmental problems affecting our state, including high asthma rates, rising sea levels that threaten coastal communities, and changes to vital ecosystems that impact Maine's economy. In 2015, NRCM participated in a lengthy stakeholder process to develop a comprehensive solar policy for Maine. We used our outreach, communications, presentations, and events to educate the public about the benefits of solar energy and build broad support for more solar. We promoted a Public Utilities Commission (PUC) study that described how Maine stands to reap economic and environmental benefits from solar energy: cheaper power for all ratepayers, lower costs for our electricity grid, more stable prices, and less air and carbon pollution. We distributed a video we created featuring Maine businesses and residents that are benefitting from solar and helped defeat proposals to terminate Maine's Renewable Energy Portfolio Standard (RPS), repeal Maine's net metering policy for solar energy installations, and cut funding for energy efficiency investments. NRCM also defended against a proposal to divert a large portion of Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI) funds away from energy efficiency investments.

column40: TO FUEL THE QUALITY AND QUANTITY OF MENTORING RELATIONSHIPS FOR AMERICA'S YOUNG PEOPLE AND TO CLOSE THE MENTORING GAP.
column80: MENTOR'S MISSION IS TO FUEL THE QUALITY AND QUANTITY OF MENTORING RELATIONSHIPS FOR AMERICA'S YOUNG PEOPLE AND TO CLOSE THE MENTORING GAP. MENTOR DRIVES THE INVESTMENT OF TIME AND MONEY INTO HIGH IMPACT MENTORING PROGRAMS THROUGH ADVOCACY, INFLUENCE STRATEGY AND PUBLIC AWARENESS. column84: MENTORING PARTNERSHIP NETWORK SUPPORT & DEVELOPMENT:MENTOR HAS BUILT AND FOSTERED A NETWORK OF AFFILIATE MENTORING PARTNERSHIPS (MPS) ACROSS THE COUNTRY TO DELIVER TRAINING AND CONSULTING TO YOUTH MENTORING PROGRAMS OF ALL TYPES AND SIZES. MENTORING PARTNERSHIPS SERVE AS STRATEGIC LOCAL FIELD-BUILDING PARTNERS, ADVANCE VOLUNTEER RECRUITMENT, BUILD PUBLIC AWARENESS, AND PROVIDE A UNIFIED VOICE FOR ADVOCACY AND POLICY, ULTIMATELY IN AN EFFORT TO OPTIMIZE OUTCOMES FOR YOUTH AND EXPAND MENTORING SERVICES TO YOUNG PEOPLE. MENTOR SUPPORTS ITS NETWORK OF AFFILIATE MENTORING PARTNERSHIPS THROUGH KNOWLEDGE SHARING, NETWORK EFFICIENCIES, AND LOCAL-NATIONAL OPPORTUNITIES. MENTORING PARTNERSHIPS ARE THE KEY INFORMANT AND DISTRIBUTION CHAIN FOR MENTOR. IN 2015 MENTOR CONTINUED TO SUPPORT THE ILLINOIS MENTORING PARTNERSHIP LAUNCHED IN 2012 AND MENTOR NEW YORK. MENTOR ALSO PROVIDED MPS THE OPPORTUNITY TO EXCHANGE SUCCESSFUL STRATEGIES FOR ENHANCING THE FIELD OF YOUTH MENTORING AT THE 2015 STATES CAUCUS WHICH WAS ATTENDED BY 50 ATTENDEES FROM 24 MPS. ADDITIONALLY, MENTOR LAUNCHED THE AMERICORPS VISTA ASPIRE MENTORING CORPS THROUGH A PUBLIC-PRIVATE PARTNERSHIP WITH AT&T AND THE CORPORATION FOR NATIONAL AND COMMUNITY SERVICE. THE ASPIRE MENTORING CORPS PROVIDED INCREASED CAPACITY FOR OUR NETWORK OF AFFILIATE MENTORING PARTNERSHIPS TO ADVANCE KEY SERVICES TO THE MENTORING FIELD AND BUILD STRONGER BRIDGES TO THE PRIVATE SECTOR.
column88: PROMOTION, PUBLIC EDUCATION & POLICY:MENTOR EDUCATES THE GENERAL PUBLIC, POLICYMAKERS, AND THE PRIVATE SECTOR ABOUT THE EFFECTIVENESS OF MENTORING AS A PROVEN STRATEGY FOR HELPING YOUNG PEOPLE BECOME SUCCESSFUL ADULTS AND SEEKS INCREASED SYSTEMIC INTEGRATION OF MENTORING. ANNUAL ACTIVITIES INCLUDE LEADING THE ANNUAL PUBLIC AWARENESS CAMPAIGN NATIONAL MENTORING MONTH IN JANUARY, CONVENING THE NATIONAL MENTORING SUMMIT, THE ONLY NATIONAL CONFERENCE FOR THE MENTORING FIELD INCLUDING PRACTITIONERS, RESEARCHERS, AND LEADERS FROM THE PRIVATE AND PUBLIC SECTORS, AS WELL AS ADVOCATING FOR EXPANDING QUALITY MENTORING PROGRAMS WITH CONGRESS AND THE ADMINISTRATION. 2015 MARKED MENTOR'S 25TH ANNIVERSARY. MENTOR CELEBRATED THIS MILESTONE BY HOSTING AN EVENT IN NYC WHICH INTRODUCED NEW SUPPORTERS TO OUR WORK AND REENGAGED LAPSED SUPPORTERS WITH THE ORGANIZATION. MENTOR ALSO SAW A 13% INCREASE IN ATTENDANCE AT THE 2015 NATIONAL MENTORING SUMMIT (880 INDIVIDUALS PARTICIPATED IN THE CONFERENCE). IN AN EFFORT TO BE SEEN AS A ONE STOP RESOURCE FOR BUILDING QUALITY MENTORING EFFORTS AND ADVANCING THE MENTORING MOVEMENT MENTOR IMPLEMENTED A BRAND REFRESH AND LAUNCHED A NEW WEBSITE. MENTOR ALSO WORKED TO DEVELOP A CAUSE ELEVATING CAMPAIGN CALLED IN REAL LIFE (LAUNCHED DURING 2016 NATIONAL MENTORING MONTH) IN PARTNERSHIP WITH THE NBA FAMILY. AS PART OF THE CAMPAIGN SEVERAL NBA PLAYERS RELEASED VIDEOS AND SHARED THEM WITH THEIR SOCIAL MEDIA NETWORKS. BEYOND THE NBA, WORK WITH THE WHITE HOUSE LED TO SOME OTHER OPPORTUNITIES WITH CELEBRITIES INTERESTED IN ELEVATING MY BROTHER'S KEEPER AND MENTORING INCLUDING A VIDEO FROM HIP HOP ARTIST KENDRICK LAMAR. TO EXPAND NATIONAL PRIVATE SECTOR ENGAGEMENT AND CLIENT SERVICES MENTOR PARTNERED WITH EY TO RELEASE A REPORT CALLED "MENTORING: AT THE CROSSROADS OF EDUCATION, BUSINESS AND COMMUNITY" AT THE 2015 SUMMIT. KEY NEW ENGAGEMENTS HAVE BEEN LAUNCHED WITH JPMORGAN CHASE & CO., DELOITTE, AND AT&T. MENTOR HAS ALSO CONTINUED TO BUILD AND DEVELOP STRATEGIC PARTNERSHIPS WITH DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION (GROWTH MINDSET FOR MENTORS, SUCCESS MENTORS), MY BROTHER'S KEEPER ALLIANCE (NATIONAL TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE PROVIDER ON MENTORING FOR BOYS AND YOUNG MEN OF COLOR), AND LINKEDIN (CAMPAIGN PARTNER PROMOTING MENTORING).
column96: PRODUCT AND PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT:ONE OF MENTOR'S CORE PRIORITIES IS TO DRIVE EXCELLENCE AND RIGOR SO THAT THE QUALITY & QUANTITY OF MENTORING AND MENTORING EXPERIENCES ARE ENHANCED ACROSS THOUSANDS OF PROGRAMS IN AMERICA. MENTOR DOES THIS BY ESTABLISHING NATIONALLY RECOGNIZED STANDARDS FOR SAFE AND EFFECTIVE MENTORING PROGRAMS CALLED THE ELEMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRACTICE FOR MENTORING , DEVELOPING TOOLS TO DISSEMINATE THESE EVIDENCED-BASED PRACTICES AND SHARE INNOVATION ACROSS THE MENTORING FIELD, OPERATING THE ONLY NATIONAL DATABASE FOR VOLUNTEER MENTORING OPPORTUNITIES, AND INFORMING AND IMPLEMENTING NEW RESEARCH TO INCREASE AND ENHANCE THE IMPACT OF QUALITY MENTORING PROGRAMS ACROSS THE COUNTRY. IN 2015, MENTOR, RELEASED THE 4TH EDITION OF THE "ELEMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRACTICE FOR MENTORING" TO REFLECT THE MOST UP-TO-DATE RESEARCH, PRACTICE, AND THINKING IN THE MENTORING FIELD. IN THE FIRST MONTH ONLINE, IT WAS DOWNLOADED MORE THAN 2,500 TIMES. TO HELP MENTORING PROGRAMS APPLY THE STANDARDS OF PRACTICE OUTLINED IN THE "ELEMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRACTICE FOR MENTORING", MENTOR CONTINUED THE ROLL OUT OF THE NATIONAL QUALITY MENTORING SYSTEM, A NATIONAL ASSESSMENT AND IMPROVEMENT PROCESS, ACROSS THEIR AFFILIATE MENTORING PARTNERSHIP NETWORK AND CREATED A SPECIAL BADGE TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL VISIBILITY, RECOGNITION, ACCOUNTABILITY AND A LEVEL OF USEFULNESS TO ALL STAKEHOLDERS, AND PARTICULARLY HELPS THOSE SEEKING TO IDENTIFY VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES. MENTOR ALSO CONTINUED TO FACILITATE THE COLLABORATIVE MENTORING WEBINAR SERIES (CMWS), MONTHLY EDUCATIONAL WEBINARS GEARED TOWARD MENTORING PROGRAM AND YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PRACTITIONERS. IN 2015 THE CMWS AVERAGED 520 REGISTRANTS EACH MONTH FROM 50 STATES AND 27 INTERNATIONAL LOCATIONS. MENTOR IS ALSO IN THE THIRD YEAR OF MANAGING THE OJJDP NATIONAL MENTORING RESOURCE CENTER (NMRC), WHICH CONSISTS OF THREE PARTS: AN ONLINE RESOURCE FOR MENTORING PROGRAMS, RESEARCH BOARD REVIEW OF RESOURCES, AND THE PROVISION OF RESEARCH INFUSED TRAINING AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE. SINCE LAUNCHING THE NMRC, MENTOR HAS RECEIVED 516 ONLINE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE REQUESTS. IN THE PAST YEAR ALONE, 13,118 USERS VISITED THE NMRC WEBSITE - 66% BEING NEW VISITORS.

column40: THE ORGANIZATION'S MISSION IS TO MOBILIZE THE NORTHWEST TO BECOME INCREASINGLY ENERGY EFFICIENT FOR A SUSTAINABLE FUTURE. BY WORKING TOGETHER THROUGH NEEA, LOCAL UTILITIES ACHIEVE REGIONAL ECONOMIES OF SCALE, MARKET LEVERAGE AND RISK POOLING TO ENCOURAGE MARKETPLACE ADOPTION OF NEW TECHNOLOGIES, SERVICES AND BUSINESS PRACTICES.

column84: MARKET EXECUTION:IN PARTNERSHIP WITH THE REGION, NEEA USES THE MARKET POWER OF THE NORTHWEST'S 13 MILLION ENERGY CONSUMERS TO ACCELERATE THE INNOVATION AND ADOPTION OF ENERGY-EFFICIENT PRODUCTS, SERVICES AND PRACTICES. SOME KEY RESULTS STEMMING FROM THE REGION'S INVESTMENT ARE: -REGIONAL MARKET SHARE OF DUCTLESS HEAT PUMPS IN THE TARGETED SINGLE-FAMILY HOME MARKET GREW FROM NEAR 0% IN 2008 TO 9.8% IN 2015. -ALMOST 5,000 HEAT PUMP WATER HEATERS WERE INSTALLED IN THE REGION IN 2015, A 60% INCREASE OVER THE YEAR BEFORE. -REGIONAL MARKET SHARE OF 28W T8 LAMPS GREW FROM 8 TO 14% IN 2015 AND ENROLLMENT IN NEEA'S REDUCED WATTAGE LAMP REPLACEMENT PROGRAM MORE THAN DOUBLED. -THE REGION COMPLETED THE FIRST REGIONAL STRATEGIC MARKET PLAN FOR THE COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL LIGHTING MARKET, WHICH INCLUDES A SHARED VISION, MISSION, GOALS, STRATEGIES FOR ADVANCING EFFICIENCY IN THIS MARKT OVER THE NEXT 20 YEARS. -INITIATED THE FIRST REGIONAL NATURAL GAS MARKET TRANSFORMATION EFFORT IN THE COUNTRY.
column88: TECHNOLOGY AND PRODUCT MANAGEMENT:NEEA SCANS THE MARKET FOR ENERGY EFFICIENCY OPPORTUNITIES AND DRIVES ACCEPTANCE AND AVAILABILITY OF PROMISING EMERGING TECHNOLOGIES. IN 2015, NEEA STAFF UNDERTOOK RESEARCH AND CONDUCTED LAB AND FIELD TESTS OF EMERGING TECHNOLOGIES, INCLUDING: -INVESTIGATING EMERGING ENERGY EFFICIENCY OPPORTUNITIES REPRESENTING TECHNICAL SAVINGS POTENTIAL FOR THE REGION OF MORE THAN 1,400 AVERAGE MEGAWATTS (AMW). -CONDUCTING INDEPENDENT TESTING AND SUPPORTING THE INTRODUCTION OF THE FIRST HEAT PUMP DRYER ON THE U.S. MARKET. -CONDUCTING LAB AND FIELD-TESTING OF THREE COMBINATION SPACE AND WATER HEATING SYSTEMS (A DUCTLESS HEAT PUMP COMBINED WITH A HEAT PUMP WATER HEATER), A CO2 HEAT PUMP WATER HEATER, AND A GAS FIRED HEAT PUMP WATER HEATER.
column96: MARKET RESEARCH, PLANNING AND EVALUATION:NEEA'S MARKET RESEARCH DRIVES PROGRAMMING, DEFINES CHALLENGES WITHIN ENERGY EFFICIENCY WORK, AND PROVIDES CRITICAL MARKET DATA AND ANALYSES ABOUT REGIONAL ENERGY CONSUMPTION AND MARKETS FOR ITS STAKEHOLDERS. IN 2015, NEEA STAFF: -PUBLISHED 35 MARKET RESEARCH AND EVALUATION REPORTS ON BEHALF OF THE REGION, INCLUDING A MARKET CHARACTERIZATION AND BASELINE REPORT FOR LOW-WATT T8 LAMPS, THE FOURTH MARKET PROGRESS AND EVALUATION REPORT FOR NEEA'S (FORMER) TELEVISION'S INITIATIVE, AND THE NORTHWEST RESIDENTIAL LIGHTING LONG-TERM MARKET TRACKING STUDY. -LAUNCHED PLANNING FOR THE RESIDENTIAL BUILDING STOCK ASSESSMENTS (RBSA). THE RBSA WILL INFORM FUTURE ENERGY PLANNING EFFORTS, AS WELL AS ENERGY EFFICIENCY UTILITY PROGRAMS AND REBATES OFFERED BY THE REGION'S UTILITIES, THE ENERGY TRUST OF OREGON AND THE BONNEVILLE POWER ADMINISTRATION.

AT THE ANNUAL MEETING, HONORIFIC AND TRAVEL AWARDS ARE PRESENTED.

column40: To advance laws and policies to improve the lives and opportunities of people living in poverty
column80: The Sargent Shriver National Center on Poverty Law (the Shriver Center) is an Illinois not-for-profit corporation that provides national leadership in advancing laws and policies that secure justice to improve the lives and opportunities of people living in poverty.
column84: The Shriver Center's Advocacy Program pursues justice for low-income people, poor communities, and communities of color. Our advocates work with community organizations, service providers, legislators, and other allies at both the federal and state level to achieve high-level, systemic policy changes that advance justice and opportunity. We lead the Legal Impact Network, a group of the strongest advocacy organizations across 32 states working to address poverty and racial inequality. We coordinate multi-state strategies to win policy and legal victories for people living in poverty.
column88: The Shriver Center's Advocate Resources and Training Program builds the skills and capacities of equal justice advocates, thereby increasing their impact. Our Leadership Institute equips new and emerging leaders to lead and advance social change agendas. Our Racial Justice Training Institute is a groundbreaking national leadership program rooted in a commitment to race equity as an integral and essential part of anti-poverty advocacy. Our Clearinghouse Community offers advocates a place to connect with one another and find important tools and resources to advance their work.

column40: CCA is organized for the purpose of promoting and advancing the preservation, conservation and protection of the marine, animal and plant life and resources of the coastal areas of the United States, both onshore and offshore, for the benefit and enjoyment of the general public. Such objectives will be accomplished by: (a) Sponsoring and encouraging research relating to marine life and environmental factors influencing its survival; (b) Educating the general public on the preservation and conservation of marine life and resources; (c) Mobilizing the general public toward the adoption of sound conservation practices conducive to the preservation of marine life and resources; (d) Formulating and encouraging the adoption of conservation programs (non-legislative) by federal and state agencies, conservation and environmental organizations, and sport and commercial fishing organizations, and assisting such agencies and organizations in the implementation of such programs.
column80: CCA is organized for the purpose of promoting and advancing the preservation, conservation and protection of the marine, animal and plant life and resources of the coastal areas of the United States, both onshore and offshore, for the benefit and enjoyment of the general public. Such objectives will be accomplished by: (a) Sponsoring and encouraging research relating to marine life and environmental factors influencing its survival; (b) Educating the general public on the preservation and conservation of marine life and resources; (c) Mobilizing the general public toward the adoption of sound conservation practices conducive to the preservation of marine life and resources; (d) Formulating and encouraging the adoption of conservation programs (non-legislative) by federal and state agencies, conservation and environmental organizations, and sport and commercial fishing organizations, and assisting such agencies and organizations in the implementation of such programs.
column84: Numerous programs focusing on habitat management and restoration, enforcement, research, education and passage of pro-resource legislation including restoration of oyster reefs and oyster populations, augmentation of species via hatchery programs, creation of artificial reefs, sea grass and mangrove plantings, donation of equipment to enforcement agencies including boats, bullet proof vests, night vision equipment, video equipment, etc., graduate and undergraduate scholarships in the marine science areas of study, catch and release mortality practices, tagging studies, etc. Pro-resource legislation includes the passing of sensible regulations such as size, slot and bag limits, gear restriction, seasonal closures in spawning areas, game fish status, licensing requirements, etc.
column88: Publication of TIDE magazine & Rising Tide newsletter and distribution to nearly 100,000 members. The publications educate the membership about conservation issues and promote responsible utilization of marine resources.
column96: Publication and distribution of state chapter newsletters to members. The newsletters inform the membership of local conservation and fisheries management issues.

column40: THE MISSION OF THE COASTAL CONSERVATION LEAGUE IS TO PROTECT THE THREATENED RESOURCES OF THE SOUTH CAROLINA COASTAL PLAIN - ITS NATURAL LANDSCAPES, ABUNDANT WILDLIFE, CLEAN WATER, AND QUALITY OF LIFE - BY WORKING WITH CITIZENS AND GOVERNMENT ON PROACTIVE, COMPREHENSIVE SOLUTIONS TO ENVIRONMENTAL CHALLENGES.
column80: THE MISSION OF THE COASTAL CONSERVATION LEAGUE IS TO PROTECT THE THREATENED RESOURCES OF THE SOUTH CAROLINA COASTAL PLAIN - ITS NATURAL LANDSCAPES, ABUNDANT WILDLIFE, CLEAN WATER, AND QUALITY OF LIFE - BY WORKING WITH CITIZENS AND GOVERNMENT ON PROACTIVE, COMPREHENSIVE SOLUTIONS TO ENVIRONMENTAL CHALLENGES.
column84: SINCE 1989, THE COASTAL CONSERVATION LEAGUE HAS BEEN PROTECTING THE SOUTH CAROLINA COASTAL PLAIN-ITS NATURAL LANDSCAPES, ABUNDANT WILDLIFE, CLEAN WATER, AND QUALITY OF LIFE-BY WORKING WITH CITIZENS AND GOVERNMENT ON COMPREHENSIVE SOLUTIONS TO ENVIRONMENTAL CHALLENGES. OUR STAFF WORKS THROUGH FOUR MAIN PROGRAM AREAS: LAND & COMMUNITIES; FOOD & AGRICULTURE; AIR, WATER, & PUBLIC HEALTH; AND ENERGY. DURING 2015, WE HAD MANY ACCOMPLISHMENTS AND MOVED MANY PROJECTS FORWARD. OUR WORK AT THE LEGISLATURE AND IN CITY AND COUNTY COUNCILS OFTEN TAKES YEARS, AND SOMETIMES DECADES. BELOW ARE SOME HIGHLIGHTS FROM 2015 BY PROGRAM AREA: FOOD & AGRICULTURE: GROWFOOD CAROLINA, OUR FOOD HUB, EXCEEDED THEIR 2015 SALES GOAL, EXPANDING OUR LOCAL FOOD SUPPLY RADIUS TO THE ENTIRE STATE. INVENTORY NOW INCLUDES FRUIT, VEGETABLES, NUTS, GRAINS, DAIRY, EGGS, AND CANOLA OIL.
column88: ENERGY: THROUGH OUTREACH AND EDUCATION OF ELECTED OFFICIALS, THE CONSERVATION LEAGUE PLAYED AN INTEGRAL ROLE IN SUPPORTING THE PASSAGE OF TWENTY-FOUR (24) OFFICIAL RESOLUTIONS OPPOSING OFFSHORE OIL AND GAS EXPLORATION AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE ATLANTIC. EVERY COASTAL MUNICIPALITY FROM NORTH MYRTLE BEACH TO HILTON HEAD IS INCLUDED IN THIS LIST. IN JULY, THE CONSERVATION LEAGUE CO-HOSTED AN ANTI-OFFSHORE DRILLING EVENT IN MOUNT PLEASANT FEATURING COMMENTS FROM SC SEN. CHIP CAMPSEN AND U.S. REP. MARK SANFORD, TO A CROWD OF MORE THAN 200 PEOPLE. AS A RESULT OF PUBLIC PRESSURE, PRESIDENT OBAMA AGREED TO PROHIBIT OFFSHORE DRILLING ALONG THE ENTIRE EASTERN SEABOARD. GOVERNOR HALEY APPOINTED CONSERVATION LEAGUE STAFF TO AN OFFSHORE ENERGY ADVISORY COMMITTEE THAT WILL BEGIN MEETING NEXT YEAR.
column96: LAND & COMMUNITIES: WORKING WITH MEMBERS OF THE COMMUNITY, WE SUCCESSFULLY THWARTED EFFORTS TO ADD MORE COMMERCIAL DEVELOPMENT TO THE ASHLEY RIVER HISTORIC DISTRICT. FURTHER, DORCHESTER COUNTY PLANNING COMMISSION IS NOW CONSIDERING CHANGES THAT TIGHTEN REGULATIONS FOR FUTURE COMMERCIAL DEVELOPMENT NEAR THE DISTRICT. THROUGH A COLLABORATIVE APPROACH INVOLVING INDUSTRY AND CONSERVATION INTERESTS, THE COASTAL CONSERVATION LEAGUE WORKED ON AN AGREEMENT WITH VOLVO WHICH WILL RESULT IN THE RESTORATION AND PROTECTION OF 2,458 ACRES OF LAND CRITICAL TO PROTECTING ONE OF SOUTH CAROLINA'S NATURAL TREASURES, FOUR HOLE SWAMP. WE WILL CONTINUE TO WORK WITH OUR PARTNERS TO ENCOURAGE AND LEAD THIS TYPE OF LANDSCAPE-SCALE MITIGATION IN THE FUTURE.

BY EMPOWERING, CONNECTING, AND ACTIVATING LEADERS ACROSS THE CLIMATE MOVEMENT, BFP IS HELPING TO BUILD A FORCE THAT CAN CONFRONT THE FOSSIL FUEL INDUSTRY AND SHOW OUR LEADERS THAT WE DEMAND BOLD ACTION IN THIS TIME OF CRISIS. OUR TWO LARGEST PROGRAMS ARE STUDENT LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT/CAMPUS DIVESTMENT AND 350 MASSACHUSETTS.CAMPUS DIVESTMENT:AFTER PROVIDING DEDICATED CAMPUS SUPPORT TO STUDENT LEADERS AT OVER TWELVE UNIVERSITIES IN MASSACHUSETTS, OUR BIGGEST SUCCESS IN 2015 WAS SUPPORTING STUDENTS IN SECURING COMMITMENTS BY LESLEY UNIVERSITY TO DIVEST ITS DIRECT HOLDINGS OF FOSSIL FUELS IN THE SPRING AND THE UNIVERSITY OF MASSACHUSETTS ANNOUNCING THAT THEY WOULD DIVEST THEIR ENDOWMENT FROM COAL IN THE FALL OF 2015.350 MASSACHUSETTS FOR A BETTER FUTURE:IN 2015, BFP SUPPORTED 350 MASS IN MAKING A LAST-DITCH EFFORT TO SUPPORT CAPE WIND AND DEMONSTRATE DEEP AND BROAD SUPPORT FOR OFFSHORE WIND IN THE STATE, CO-FOUNDED AND HELPED LEAD THE COALITION FOR A CLEAN ENERGY FUTURE TO PROMOTE CARBON PRICING IN THE STATE, CO-FOUNDED AND HELPED LEAD THE MASS POWER FORWARD COALITION, HELPED BUILD OPPOSITION TO NEW GAS PIPELINES, AND SERVED AS THE ANCHOR FOR THE 2,000+ PERSON JOBS, JUSTICE, CLIMATE EVENT - THE REGION'S LARGEST CLIMATE JUSTICE MOBILIZATION IN ITS HISTORY, AND WON FURTHER SUPPORT FOR STATE DIVESTMENT FROM UNION LEADERS.

column40: THE NOBEL PRIZE EDUCATION FUND (NPEF) IS ORGANIZED FOR THE PURPOSE OF SUPPORTING THE CHARITABLE PURPOSES OF THE NOBEL FOUNDATION, A NONPROFIT ORGANIZATION REGISTERED UNDER THE LAWS OF SWEDEN, AND ANY OF ITS AFFILIATES IN THEIR RESPECTIVE CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES. THE NOBEL FOUNDATION HAS BEEN RECOGNIZED BY THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE AS A PUBLIC CHARITY UNDER IRC SECTION 501(C)(3), AS A SECTION 509(A)(1) PUBLIC CHARITY. NPEF SUPPORTS ACTIVITIES THAT INSPIRE PEOPLE AROUND THE WORLD BY INFORMING AND EDUCATING THEM ABOUT THE EXTRAORDINARY HUMAN ACHIEVEMENTS AND INDIVIDUALS HONORED BY THE NOBEL FOUNDATION WITH A NOBEL PRIZE.
column80: The Nobel Prize Education Fund (NPEF) is organized for the purpose of supporting the charitable purposes of the Nobel Foundation, a nonprofit organization registered under the laws of Sweden, and any of its affiliates in their respective charitable activities. The Nobel Foundation has been recognized by the internal revenue service as a public charity under IRC section 501(c)(3), as a Section 509(a)(1) public charity. NPEF supports activities that inspire people around the world by informing and educating them about the extraordinary human achievements and individuals honored by The Nobel Foundation with a Nobel Prize.
column84: Nobel Peace Prize Concert: NPEF will support the Concert in Oslo, Norway - a tribute to the year's Nobel Peace Prize Laureates. The Concert is distributed to around 100 countries and serves as a vital means of spreading information and inspiration around the world related to the Nobel Prize.
column88: Nobelprize.org: NPEF will support and promote nobelprize.org, the official web site of the Nobel Foundation, focusing on its educational programs, which build public awareness and understanding of the achievements of Nobel Laureates.
column96: Nobel Center: NPEF will support the project of creating a Nobel Center - a building for cultural and scientific activities - in Stockholm, Sweden. On the basis of Alfred Nobel's last will and testament, the Nobel Prize is awarded to those who, through their discoveries and achievements, have conferred the greatest benefit on mankind. The future Nobel Center will act in the same spirit by encouraging creativity and innovation. The Prize fields, the Laureates' achievements, their life stories and the future perspectives in their fields provide a rich source of inspiration on which the Center will build its exhibitions, media productions, and activities.

column40: NEW SCHOOLS FUND'S MISSION IS TO IMPROVE PUBLIC EDUCATION.
column80: TO IMPROVE PUBLIC EDUCATION BY IDENTIFYING AND SUPPORTING THE MOST PROMISING EDUCATION VENTURES IN THE COUNTRY, AND CREATING A NATIONWIDE NETWORK OF EDUCATION ENTREPRENEURS COMMITTED TO CLOSING THE ACHIEVEMENT GAP.
column84: Venture Building: NewSchools invests in entrepreneurial organizations and fuels their success by coaching and supporting their leadership teams. On behalf of our donors, our venture team screens, reviews, and conducts full diligence on more than 100 potential investments in the course of a year. Once an investment is made, NewSchools' managing partners provide Board level management assistance to the leadership of our portfolio companies, connecting them to customers, funders, and each other. The goal of this support is to propel rapid growth, with quality, and enable our entrepreneurs to take transformative ideas for improving public education to scale.
column88: FIELD BUILDING: NEWSCHOOLS IS THE HUB OF A MOVEMENT SEEKING TO TRANSFORM THE PUBLIC EDUCATION SYSTEM SO THAT EVERY CHILD RECEIVES AN EXCELLENT EDUCATION. THROUGH OUR FIELD BUILDING WORK, INCLUDING OUR ANNUAL NEWSCHOOLS SUMMIT, WE CONNECT, INSPIRE, AND GALVANIZE EDUCATORS, THOUGHT LEADERS, POLICY MAKERS, AND PRACTITIONERS. WE HOST FREQUENT COMMUNITY OF PRACTICE MEETINGS THAT BRING OUR PORTFOLIO ENTREPRENEURS TOGETHER WITH OTHERS TO SHARE LESSONS LEARNED, DISCUSS NEW FINDINGS FROM THE FIELD, DEVELOP PARTNERSHIPS, AND EXPLORE NEW IDEAS FOR IMPROVING PUBLIC EDUCATION, ESPECIALLY FOR THE MOST UNDERSERVED CHILDREN.
column96: Fiscal Sponsorships: NEWSCHOOLS HAS PARTNERED WITH OTHER ENTREPRENEURIAL EDUCATION ORGANIZATIONS IN FISCAL SPONSORSHIPS ARRANGEMENTS, NEW SCHOOLS WILL ACCEPT RESTRICTED CONTRIBUTIONS FOR THESE PROJECTS, AND THEN SUPPORT THOSE ORGANIZATIONS AS THEY LAUNCH INTO NEW 501(C)(3) ORGANIZATIONS.

column40: BRIGHTFOCUS FOUNDATION SEEKS TO SAVE MIND AND SIGHT.
column80: BRIGHTFOCUS FOUNDATION (BRIGHTFOCUS) DRIVES INNOVATIVE RESEARCH WORLDWIDE AND PROMOTES AWARENESS OF ALZHEIMER'S, MACULAR DEGENERATIONS AND GLAUCOMA. PLEASE REFER TO SCHEDULE O FOR A COMPLETE OVERVIEW OF OUR MISSION.
column84: ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE RESEARCH (ADR) - BRIGHTFOCUS' ADR PROGRAM FUNDS RESEARCH FOCUSED ON UNDERSTANDING ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE'S CAUSES, ITS EARLY DETECTION, AND TREATMENTS TO HELP SLOW OR STOP ITS PROGRESSION, AND ULTIMATELY TO PREVENT THE DISEASE ALTOGETHER. ADR ANNUALLY AWARDS PEER-REVIEWED GRANTS TO SCIENTISTS FROM INSTITUTIONS WORLDWIDE WHO ARE CONDUCTING BIOMEDICAL AND CLINICAL RESEARCH ON ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE. DURING THE FISCAL YEAR ENDED MARCH 31, 2016, ADR FUNDED 30 NEW PROJECTS, TOTALING $6,504,817, AND AWARDED $342,500 IN TWO SPECIAL PROJECTS THAT FOCUS ON BETTER USE OF MODERN TECHNOLOGIES, INCLUDING MOBILE TECHNOLOGIES AND BIG DATA, TO INCREASE THE SPEED OF CLINICAL TRIALS AND RESEARCH PROGRESS. SINCE INCEPTION, BRIGHTFOCUS HAS CONTRIBUTED MORE THAN $100 MILLION TO THE CONQUERING OF ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE. ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ABOUT SPECIFIC PROJECTS ARE INCLUDED IN SCHEDULES F & I. BRIGHTFOCUS IS HONORED TO HAVE SUPPORTED THE EARLY RESEARCH OF TWO EVENTUAL NOBEL PRIZE WINNERS: DR. STANLEY PRUSINER AND DR. PAUL GREENGARD, WHOSE WORK HAS BEEN INSTRUMENTAL TO OUR CURRENT UNDERSTANDING OF ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE. FURTHER ILLUSTRATING BRIGHTFOCUS' IMPACT, A THIRD-PARTY ROSTER OF PAPERS THAT CONSIDERED MILESTONES IN ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE LISTS 19 BRIGHTFOCUS-SUPPORTED PAPERS, SIX PERCENT OF THE TOTAL RECOGNIZED. BRIGHTFOCUS CONTINUES ITS PARTNERSHIP WITH THE ACADEMIC JOURNAL "MOLECULAR NEURODEGENERATION" AS THE OFFICIAL JOURNAL OF THE BRIGHTFOCUS FOUNDATION. THE JOURNAL PUBLISHES TECHNICAL PAPERS RELATED TO NEURODEGENERATION IN THE THREE DISEASE AREAS. AS AN "OPEN ACCESS" JOURNAL, THERE IS NO FEE FOR READERS, AND ALL CONTENT IS FREE OF CHARGE AND EASY TO ACCESS. THIS OPEN ACCESS ENSURES MAXIMAL REACH OF JOURNAL CONTENTS TO SCIENTISTS AND CARE PROVIDERS WORLDWIDE. MOLECULAR NEURODEGENERATION IS CURRENTLY THE HIGHEST IMPACT OPEN ACCESS JOURNAL IN THE NEUROSCIENCES.ADR-SUPPORTED RESEARCH CONTINUED TO MAKE THE NEWS IN THIS FISCAL YEAR, INCLUDING HIGH VISIBILITY REPORTS RELATING TO DEVELOPMENT OF A NEW CLASS OF ANTI-ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE DRUGS, INTERDISCIPLINARY RESEARCH BRIDGING ALZHEIMER'S AND OTHER CONDITIONS, AND MANY OTHER TOPICS. EACH AREA OF RESEARCH IS THE SUBJECT OF ONGOING BRIGHTFOCUS FUNDED RESEARCH STUDIES. MORE DETAILS ARE AVAILABLE IN THE NEWS UPDATES SECTION OF THE BRIGHTFOCUS.ORG WEBSITE.IN ADDITION TO SUPPORTING CUTTING-EDGE RESEARCH, ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE RESEARCH PROVIDES EXCELLENT RESOURCES ON DETECTING, TREATING, AND LIVING WITH THE DISEASE. ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE IS THE ONLY CAUSE OF DEATH AMONG THE TOP 10 IN AMERICA WITHOUT A WAY TO PREVENT, CURE, OR EVEN SLOW ITS PROGRESSION. IT IS AN IRREVERSIBLE DEGENERATION OF THE BRAIN THAT CAUSES DISRUPTIONS IN MEMORY, COGNITION, PERSONALITY, AND OTHER FUNCTIONS AND INEVITABLY LEADS TO DEATH. MORE THAN 5 MILLION AMERICANS AGED 65 AND OLDER ARE THOUGHT TO HAVE ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE TODAY, AND THAT NUMBER IS EXPECTED TO TRIPLE BY MIDCENTURY.
column88: MACULAR DEGENERATION RESEARCH (MDR)- A PROGRAM OF BRIGHTFOCUS, HAS AWARDED MORE THAN $21.5 MILLION TO SCIENTISTS STUDYING THE DISEASE. THE LATEST RESEARCH IS FOCUSED ON NOVEL TREATMENTS FOR THE DISEASE, UNDERSTANDING ITS CAUSES AND PROGRESSION, DRUG THERAPIES, AND NEW SCREENING TECHNIQUES.DURING THE FISCAL YEAR ENDING MARCH 31, 2016, MDR AWARDED $2,944,963 IN PEER-REVIEWED GRANT AWARDS TO 19 NEW RESEARCH PROJECTS AND $100,000 TO A SPECIAL PROJECT THAT RANGE FROM STUDIES TO DEVELOP NEW ANTI-OXIDANT BASED THERAPIES TO CLINICAL PROJECTS TESTING ADVANCED DIAGNOSTIC STRATEGIES. ADDITIONAL DETAILS ABOUT SPECIFIC PROJECTS ARE INCLUDED IN SCHEDULES F & I. MDR-FUNDED PROJECTS WERE FEATURED IN MEDIA ARTICLES, INCLUDING PROGRESS IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF NEW THERAPIES, AND INTERDISCIPLINARY RESEARCH COMBINING AGE-RELATED MACULAR DEGENERATION (AMD) KNOWLEDGE WITH VASCULAR BIOLOGY TO DISCOVER NEW TREATMENT OPPORTUNITIES FOR MACULAR DEGENERATION. MORE DETAILS ON THIS AND OTHER SUCCESSFUL OUTCOMES ACHIEVED THROUGH MDR FUNDING ARE AVAILABLE IN THE NEWS UPDATES SECTION OF THE BRIGHTFOCUS.ORG WEBSITE.IN ADDITION TO SUPPORTING CUTTING-EDGE RESEARCH, MACULAR DEGENERATION RESEARCH PROVIDES EXCELLENT RESOURCES ON DETECTING, TREATING, AND LIVING WITH THIS DISEASE. AGE-RELATED MACULAR DEGENERATION IS A LEADING CAUSE OF VISION LOSS IN THE UNITED STATES. IT DESTROYS THE MACULA, THE PART OF THE EYE THAT PROVIDES SHARP, CENTRAL VISION NEEDED FOR SEEING OBJECTS CLEARLY. THE MOST COMMON EYE CONDITION IN PEOPLE AGE 60 AND OLDER, IT CAN LEAD TO VISION LOSS IN ONE OR BOTH EYES, MAKING IT DIFFICULT TO RECOGNIZE FACES, DRIVE A CAR, OR READ.
column96: NATIONAL GLAUCOMA RESEARCH (NGR)- BRIGHTFOCUS' NATIONAL GLAUCOMA RESEARCH (NGR) PROGRAM HAS AWARDED MORE THAN $28.6 MILLION WORLDWIDE FOR THE STUDY OF GLAUCOMA. NGR-SUPPORTED RESEARCH HAS BEEN FOCUSED ON THE EYE-BRAIN CONNECTION, THE MECHANISMS FOR PRESSURE BUILDUP IN THE EYE, PREVENTING DAMAGE TO THE OPTIC NERVE, AND UNDERSTANDING THE ROLE GENES PLAY IN ORDER TO DEVELOP EARLY GLAUCOMA SCREENING AND TARGETED TREATMENTS. NGR GRANTS ARE AVAILABLE TO GLAUCOMA RESEARCHERS WORLDWIDE. NGR PLACES SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON ENCOURAGING APPLICATIONS FROM YOUNG SCIENTISTS AND THOSE WITH CUTTING-EDGE IDEAS. ANNUAL GRANT APPLICATIONS ARE PEER-REVIEWED, AND RECIPIENT SELECTIONS ARE BASED ON SCIENTIFIC MERIT. DURING THE FISCAL YEAR ENDING MARCH 31, 2016, NGR AWARDED $1,874,555 FOR 13 NEW PROJECTS THAT RANGE FROM CALCULATING INDIVIDUAL RISK FOR GLAUCOMA TO REAL-TIME MONITORING AND CONTROL OF PRESSURE IN THE EYE, A SIGNIFICANT RISK FACTOR FOR GLAUCOMA ADDITIONAL DETAILS ABOUT SPECIFIC PROJECTS ARE INCLUDED IN SCHEDULES F & I.NGR-FUNDED RESEARCH WAS RECOGNIZED BY THE MEDIA THIS YEAR, INCLUDING AN NGR-SUPPORTED STRATEGY TO IMPROVING GENE THERAPY OPPORTUNITIES IN GLAUCOMA. MORE DETAILS ARE AVAILABLE IN THE NEWS UPDATES SECTION OF THE BRIGHTFOCUS.ORG WEBSITE.IN ADDITION TO SUPPORTING CUTTING-EDGE RESEARCH, NATIONAL GLAUCOMA RESEARCH PROVIDES EXCELLENT RESOURCES ON DETECTING, TREATING, AND LIVING WITH THE DISEASE. GLAUCOMA IS A GROUP OF DISEASES THAT DAMAGE THE EYE'S OPTIC NERVE AND CAN RESULT IN VISION LOSS AND PERMANENT BLINDNESS. MORE THAN 3 MILLION AMERICANS AGE 40 AND OLDER HAVE GLAUCOMA. MORE THAN 60 MILLION PEOPLE IN THE WORLD HAVE THE DISEASE, AND THAT NUMBER IS EXPECTED TO INCREASE BY AS MUCH AS 20 MILLION BY 2020. WITH EARLY DETECTION AND TREATMENT, GLAUCOMA OFTEN CAN BE MANAGED TO PROTECT EYES FROM MORE SERIOUS VISION LOSS, BUT IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ONLY HALF OF THE PEOPLE LIVING WITH GLAUCOMA ARE AWARE THAT THEY HAVE THE DISEASE.

column40: Protect, restore, and sustain Washington's environment.
column80: Our mission is to protect, restore, and sustain Washington's environment.
column84: PEOPLE FOR PUGET SOUND -The People for Puget Sound program is focused on reducing the flow of polluted runoff into Puget Sound, reducing the risk of an oil spill into Puget Sound, protecting Puget Sound habitats, and building public support and political will for the protection and restoration of Puget Sound.
column88: CLIMATE AND CLEAN ENERGY -The Climate and Clean Energy Agenda is focused on reducing global warming pollution, promoting clean renewable energy, increasing energy efficiency and creating clean green jobs.
column96: EVERGREEN FORESTS -WEC's Evergreen Forests program works to ensure Washington has a strong regulatory and policy framework that guides the responsible management of state and private forests. Additionally, through our Growing Our Future campaign, we are working to improve the management of Washington's private forests by providing landowners with financial incentives for approaches that better protect clean water, habitat, and mitigate climate pollution. This program is an exciting intersection of WEC's climate campaign, clean water work, and longtime commitment to forest protection.

column40: WORKERS DEFENSE PROJECT IS A MEMBERSHIP BASED ORGANIZATION THAT EMPOWERS LOW-INCOME WORKERS TO ACHIEVE FAIR EMPLOYMENT THROUGH EDUCATION, DIRECT SERVICES, ORGANIZING, AND STRATEGIC PARTNERSHIPS.
column80: WORKERS DEFENSE PROJECT IS A MEMBERSHIP BASED ORGANIZATION THAT EMPOWERS

THIS PROGRAM CREATES A PATHWAY FOR INDIVIDUAL JUSTICE AS WELL AS COMMUNITY INVOLVEMENT AS MEMBERS ARE EMPOWERED THROUGH THEIR WORK ON INDIVIDUAL CASES, THEY LEARN MORE ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF CIVIC ENGAGEMENT AND THE NEED FOR SYSTEMIC CHANGE IN THE CONSTRUCTION INDUSTRY. SPECIFICALLY, ELS SUPPORTS WORKERS BY A)EDUCATING WORKERS ON EMPLOYMENT ISSUES INCLUDING BASIC WORKERS' RIGHTS, SAFETY, DISCRIMINATION, AND THE FAMILY MEDICAL LEAVE ACT; B) RECOVERING WAGES FOR WORKERS WHO HAVE BEEN DENIED PAYMENT FOR THEIR WORK; C)HELPING INJURED WORKERS RECEIVE MEDICAL ATTENTION AND COMPENSATION; D)WORKING WITH PUBLIC AGENCIES INCLUDING LAW ENFORCEMENT, DEPARTMENT OF LABOR, OSHA AND THE TEXAS WORKFORCE COMMISSION TO IMPROVE ENFORCEMENT OF EXISTING WORKER PROTECTION POLICIES AND ENSURE LOW-WAGE WORKER'S CASES MOVE FORWARD IN THE SYSTEM.
column88: ADULT EDUCATION AND TRAINING: THROUGH THE ADULT EDUCATION AND TRAINING PROGRAM (AET), WDP COORDINATES ACTIVITIES TO DEVELOP THE ORGANIZING AND SELF-ADVOCACY SKILLS OF LOW-WAGE WORKERS. WDP OFFERS THE FOLLOWING CLASSES THROUGH AET - A)THE LEADERSHIP INSTITUTE WHICH TRAINS MEMBERS TO BECOME THE VOICE OF FUTURE WDP CAMPAIGNS THROUGH PUBLIC SPEAKING, DIRECT ACTION, STRATEGIC PLANNING, AND OTHER CLASSES; B)ESL COURSES WHICH ARE SIX-WEEK BEGINNER AND INTERMEDIATE COURSES THAT TEACH WORKERS TO DEVELOP
column96: RESEARCH AND POLICY: WDP USES ITS RESEARCH AND POLICY PROGRAM (RAP) TO ILLUMINATE THE DEFICIENT WORKING CONDITIONS OF CONSTRUCTION WORKERS AND TO EMPOWER WORKER- MEMBERS TO ENGAGE WITH POLICYMAKERS ABOUT CREATING SYSTEMIC CHANGE. THROUGH RAP, WDP ENGAGES ITS MEMBERS IN A)RESEARCH ON THE CONSTRUCTION INDUSTRY THAT PROVIDES DETAILED DATA TO POLICYMAKERS ABOUT WORKPLACE CONDITIONS AND OFFERS SOLUTIONS TO PERSISTENT PROBLEMS IN THE INDUSTRY; B)CIVIC PARTICIPATION THAT EMPOWERS WORKERS THROUGH VOTER

column40: CHILDREN & FAMILIES FIRST HAS HELPED NEEDY CHILDREN AND FAMILIES IN DELAWARE FOR MORE THAN 125 YEARS. ANNUALLY, THE ORGANIZATION SERVES MORE THAN 30,000 INDIVIDUALS STATEWIDE THROUGH 30+ PROGRAMS THAT OFFER ASSISTANCE AND SUPPORT THROUGHOUT THE LIFESPAN. THE ORGANIZATION'S SERVICES ARE CHILD-CENTERED AND FAMILY-FOCUSED, FORMING A COMPREHENSIVE CONTINUUM OF QUALITY SOCIAL, EDUCATIONAL, AND MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.
column80: CHILDREN & FAMILIES FIRST HELPS CHILDREN FACING ADVERSITY ON THEIR JOURNEY TO ADULTHOOD. WE USE PROVEN METHODS TO HELP FAMILIES RAISE THEIR CHILDREN SO THEY CAN FLOURISH.
column84: POSITIVE PARENTING - FAMILY FOSTER CARE IS PROVIDED TO CHILDREN AND TEENS WHO CANNOT REMAIN AT HOME DUE TO REASONS THAT MAY INCLUDE ABUSE OR NEGLECT. FOSTER FAMILIES RECEIVE EXTENSIVE TRAINING AND SUPPORT. IN 2015, 78% OF CHILDREN IN FOSTER CARE REMAINED PLACED IN ONE HOME.ADOPTION FROM FOSTER CARE PROVIDES A PERMANENT HOME FOR OLDER YOUTH, SIBLINGS, OR CHILDREN WITH SPECIAL EMOTIONAL, DEVELOPMENTAL, OR MEDICAL NEEDS WHOSE PARENTS HAVE HAD THEIR RIGHTS TERMINATED. POTENTIAL ADOPTIVE FAMILIES ARE RECRUITED, TRAINED, SELECTED, AND SUPPORTED TO FACILITATE SUCCESSFUL ADOPTIONS. IN 2015, 100% OF CHILDREN PLACED FOR ADOPTION REMAINED IN ONE HOME AND 100% OF ADOPTIONS WERE FINALIZED WITHIN 12 MONTHS.FAMILY SEARCH & ENGAGEMENT WORKS WITH YOUTH IN FOSTER CARE AGES 10 TO 17 WHO ARE AT-RISK OF AGING OUT OF FOSTER CARE EITHER TO CONNECT THEM TO FAMILY MEMBERS OR OTHER CARING ADULTS, FOR PERMANENT PLACEMENT, OR FOR SUPPORT DURING TRANSITION. OF 13 YOUTH SERVED IN 2015, 13 MADE CONNECTIONS WITH CARING ADULTS. THE STRENGTHENING FAMILIES PROGRAM OFFERS FAMILY SKILLS TRAINING, ADDRESSING THE NEEDS OF VULNERABLE FAMILIES, INCLUDING THOSE REUNITING AFTER FOSTER CARE. IN 2015, 81% DEMONSTRATED REDUCED RISK FOR NEGATIVE PARENTING BEHAVIORS ON TWO OR MORE DOMAINS.
column88: EARLY CHILDHOOD - DELAWARE STARS IS THE STATE'S QUALITY RATING SYSTEM FOR CHILD CARE, DESIGNED TO IMPROVE EARLY CARE AND EDUCATION. AS OF THE END OF 2015, THERE WERE 211 PROGRAMS ON THE CFF STARS CASELOAD. DURING 2015, 58 PROGRAMS MOVED UP A STAR LEVEL, 22 OF WHICH MOVED TO STAR LEVEL 5, THE HIGHEST RATING IN THE SYSTEM.THE CHILD AND ADULT CARE FOOD PROGRAM ASSURES THAT CHILDREN IN LICENSED CHILD CARE RECEIVE NUTRITIONALLY BALANCED MEALS. IN 2015, 1,129,193 NUTRITIOUS MEALS WERE SERVED TO CHILDREN IN THE CARE OF PARTICIPATING PROVIDERS. THE INFRASTRUCTURE FUND SUPPORTED CHILD CARE PROGRAMS TO ENHANCE FACILITIES AND/OR TECHNOLOGY TO SUPPORT QUALITY IMPROVEMENT EFFORTS RELATED TO THE DELAWARE STARS PROGRAM. IN 2015, CFF PROVIDED ASSISTANCE TO 77 CHILD CARE PROGRAMS.THE CAPACITY PROGRAM SUPPORTS CHILD CARE PROGRAMS WITH TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND SMALL GRANTS IN ORDER TO PREPARE THEM TO PARTICIPATE IN DELAWARE STARS. IN 2015, CFF PROVIDED SUPPORT TO 70 PROGRAMS.
column96: SUPPORTING TEENS - ARC (ADOLESCENT RESOURCE CENTER) IS A COMPREHENSIVE EDUCATION AND MEDICAL SERVICE FOR TEENS, DESIGNED TO DECREASE THEIR RISK-TAKING AND PROMOTE HEALTHY CHOICES. ARC EDUCATION PROVIDES EDUCATIONAL--- SESSIONS IN SCHOOLS. ARC CLINICS PROVIDE COMPREHENSIVE COUNSELING AND MEDICAL SERVICES FOR TEENS, INCLUDING CONTRACEPTION, TESTING AND TREATMENT FOR SEXUALLY TRANSMITTED DISEASES, AND PREGNANCY CONFIRMATION. IN 2015, YOUTH PARTICIPATING IN ARC EDUCATION SERVICES KNEW 89% OF INFORMATION AT POST-TEST COMPARED WITH 53% AT PRE-TEST. 98% OF YOUTH WHO WERE TESTED IN ARC CLINICS AND DIAGNOSED WITH AND STD WERE TREATED IN A TIMELY MANNER. FFT (FUNCTIONAL FAMILY THERAPY) IS AN EVIDENCE-BASED PROGRAM SERVING YOUTH BETWEEN THE AGES OF 11 AND 18 AND THEIR FAMILIES WHO ARE STRUGGLING WITH BEHAVIORAL PROBLEMS AND FAMILY CONFLICT. IN 2015, 71% OF FAMILIES SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED THE THERAPY AND 75% OF ADOLESCENTS AND PARENTS REPORTED IMPROVED RELATIONSHIPS. WE USE THE FFT MODEL IN OUR INTENSIVE OUTPATIENT PROGRAM (IOP) WHICH OFFERS A UNIQUE COMBINATION OF INDIVIDUAL AND FAMILY THERAPY IN CONJUNCTION WITH CASE MANAGEMENT AND PSYCHIATRIC CARE FOR YOUTH AND THEIR FAMILIES IN KENT AND SUSSEX COUNTIES. WE ALSO USE FFT IN THE FAMILY ASSESSMENT AND INTERVENTION RESPONSE (FAIR) PROGRAM WHICH IS PART OF THE STATE OF DELAWARE'S DIFFERENTIAL RESPONSE SYSTEM IN CHILD WELFARE. FAIR IS DESIGNED TO PREVENT TEENS FROM ENTERING FOSTER CARE THROUGH THE USE OF EVIDENCE-BASED PROGRAMMING - FFT AND FAMILY KEYS. OF THE 447 FAMILIES ASSESSED BY THE FAIR PROGRAM IN 2015, ONLY 2 YOUTH ENTERED PLACEMENT RESULTING IN A .004% PLACEMENT RATE.SEAFORD HOUSE IS A RESIDENTIAL AND DAY TREATMENT PROGRAM FOR YOUTH AGES 12 TO 17 WITH MENTAL HEALTH CONDITIONS. IN 2015, 79% OF YOUTH WERE DISCHARGED TO A LEVEL OR LESS RESTRICTIVE PLACEMENT.

column80: THE MONTANA INNOCENCE PROJECT IS DEDICATED TO EXONERATING THE INNOCENT AND PREVENTING WRONGFUL CONVICTIONS.

column40: Puente promotes the cultivation and consumption of amaranth, combined with other traditional and strategic crops, to encourage the diversification of local agriculture and diet for rural communities in Mexico as a means of improving community well-being.
column80: Puente a la Salud Comunitaria contributes to food sovereignty and advances the health and well-being of rural communities in Mexico by promoting the cultivation, consumption and commercialization of amaranth.
column84: The organization combined Healthy Families and Eco-Amaranth into one program, Farm-to-Table. The program promotes the production of amaranth in rural communities through agricultural training, technical assistance and farmer-to-farmer exchanges. Since 2007, Puente has worked with hundreds of Oaxacan farmers from indigenous communities to cultivate amaranth using sustainable and ecological practices. The Eco-Amaranth program presents subsistence farmers with the opportunity to create a healthy food source and to generate additional revenue for their families. The program collaborates with the Healthy Families team to contribute to food sovereignty and to improve family nutrition by promoting amaranth, a native crop rich in nutrients and with economic potential. Healthy Families: Puentes Healthy Families program works with indigenous communities in Oaxaca to foster a more diverse and nutritious diet for their families and help combat child malnutrition through consumption of amaranth. Since 2003, Puente has worked with over 7,500 women from over 100 communities in Oaxaca to prevent health problems and malnutrition through this program. Using a participatory approach, the program works with women from vulnerable populations to address some of the root causes of malnutrition in their communities and to make informed decisions regarding the consumption of amaranth.
column88: Social economy: Farmer families are able to sell their harvest at a higher profit by organizing microenterprises and regional networks with increased access to markets and value added technology. The program aims to derive both social and economic benefits for participants. The Program Director and staff offer trainings to micro-enterprises to increase their ability to develop and commercialize food products, based on amaranth. In addition, we support local and regional point-of-sales operations to allow the enterprises to increase their clients and direct sales.

column40: The Fund is a nonprofit organization that works to build a critical mass of great public schools in Chicago by investing in talented principals and enabling educator teams to reinvent classroom learning in ways that dramatically improve student outcomes. The Fund is a catalyst for accelerating student learning in all of Chicago's public schools, and has been a longstanding leader in identifying and scaling what works for teachers and principals, as well as the students they serve. Please visit our website at www.thefundchicago.org to learn more about The Fund.
column80: The Chicago Public Education Fund (the Fund) is building a critical mass of great public schools in Chicago by investing in talented principals and enabling educator teams to reinvent classroom learning in ways that dramatically improve student outcomes.
column84: Innovative Educator NetworkThe Fund continues to support principals and their educator teams as they use innovative models to personalize instruction, accelerate student learning and move their public schools into the 21st century. In 2015, The Fund conducted a third cycle of its Summer Design Program (SDP), which enabled 40 public school teams to take part in a summer-long workshop series designed to help them implement small-scale innovations within their classrooms and schools. Following the SDP, The Fund offered continued programmatic and financial support to 25 schools; projects supported through this initiative included the expansion of personalized and blended learning strategies; the restructuring of physical classrooms; different approaches to class schedules; new professional development and peer engagement opportunities for teachers; and more. The Fund also provided support to the Breakthrough Schools Chicago initiative, a competitive grant program to catalyze the development of transformational, 21st Century school models that enhance personalized learning and accelerate student outcomes. In 2015, The Fund provided time, space, mentors and resources for seven schools to build on early innovations and to transform teaching and learning in a way that better meets student needs. The Fund's support also helped expand this program to an additional 23 schools, creating the largest educator-led, technology-enabled initiative in the country.
column88: Principal Quality InitiativeThe Fund continues its support of increasing the number of high-performing principals in Chicago's public schools to 350 by 2018. In 2015, this included work to improve the retention of Chicago's top-performing public school principals through the Chicago Principals Fellowship. The Fellowship, which is a partnership between The Fund, Crown Family Philanthropies, Chicago Public Schools, and Northwestern University, is an executive-level leadership development program intended to grow the skills of top principals and further expand their leadership capacity. Twenty principals participated in the Fellowship during 2015; ten percent of the city's principals are intended to participate over the three-year program. The Fund also worked to inform its own and the city's efforts to improve principal quality by performing regular engagement surveys, exit surveys and focus groups with public school principals in Chicago. The Fund's surveys alone yielded a 65 percent response rate and were used to inform organizational strategy and programming. For example, with this data, The Fund published its 2015 School Leadership Report: Chicago's Fight to Keep Top Principals. The report summarized findings about the principal turnover rate in Chicago and provided four recommendations to help retain principals longer in their roles. With support from The Fund, the Chicago Public Schools Principal Quality Working Group built upon the 2015 School Leadership Report's call to improve principal supports, recommending a menu of differentiated professional development options to better meet the needs of all sitting and aspiring principals. The Fund's efforts have helped secure 212 high-quality principals leading Chicago's public schools, a more than 40 percent increase since this work began in late 2013.
column96: Educator EngagementThe Fund works to engage educators as much as possible and to establish the fundamental conditions necessary to enable high-performing principals to transform schools. In 2015, The Fund focused on elevating the stories of the city's top-performing principals through several reports, including its Summer Design Program Report and Profiles in Schools Leadership: Leveraging Student-Based Budgeting report. The Fund also invested resources in its Educator Advisory Committee (EAC), designed to inform Fund strategy and program. In 2015, the EAC included educators from public schools citywide.

column40: To protect, preserve and promote the Pacific Crest National Scenic Trail as a world-class experience for hikers and equestrians, and for all the values provided by wild and scenic lands.
column80: To protect, preserve and promote the Pacific Crest National Scenic Trail as a world-class experience for hikers and equestrians, and for all the values provided by wild and scenic lands.
column84: PRESERVE:In 2015, 1,825 citizen stewards and corps crew members performed the hard, physical labor of annual maintenance and restoration of the PCT. PCTA volunteers contributed 96,000 service hours in 2015, an in-kind value of $2.2 million. These hours included the completion of 1,482 miles of trail maintenance, 24 miles of trail reconstruction, the construction of one trailhead kiosk and 37 volunteer training events.
column88: PROMOTE:Through our print and electronic publications and personal outreach, we promote the PCT, marshal volunteers and keep our members and elected leaders informed of programs and issues facing the trail. Program service accomplishments continued on Schedule O.
column96: PROTECT:In 2015, the PCTA partnered with private foundations, land trusts, and federal agencies to purchase land from private owners that included or was adjacent to the PCT. Program service accomplishments continued on Schedule O.

column40: THE AMERICAN IMMIGRATION COUNCIL EXISTS TO PROMOTE THE PROSPERITY AND CULTURAL RICHNESS OF OUR DIVERSE NATION BY 1)EDUCATING CITIZENS ABOUT THE ENDURING CONTRIBUTIONS OF AMERICA'S IMMIGRANTS;2)STANDING UP FOR SENSIBLE AND HUMANE IMMIGRATION POLICIES THAT REFLECT AMERICAN VALUES;3)INSISTING THAT OUR IMMIGRATION LAWS BE ENACTED AND IMPLEMENTED IN A WAY THAT HONORS FUNDAMENTAL CONSTITUTIONAL AND HUMAN RIGHTS;4)WORKING TIRELESSLY TO ACHIEVE JUSTICE AND FAIRNESS FOR IMMIGRANTS UNDER THE LAW. THE AMERICAN IMMIGRATION COUNCIL BELIEVES THAT THE DIGNITY OF THE INDIVIDUAL KNOWS NO BOUNDARY. OUR NATION'S MORAL AND ETHICAL VALUES MUST BE REFLECTED IN THE WAY WE WELCOME IMMIGRANTS.
column80: THE MISSION OF THE AMERICAN IMMIGRATION COUNCIL IS TO STRENGTHEN AMERICA BY HONORING OUR IMMIGRANT HISTORY AND SHAPING HOW AMERICANS THINK ABOUT AND ACT TOWARDS IMMIGRATION NOW AND IN THE FUTURE.
column84: LEGAL DEPARTMENT: THE LEGAL DEPARTMENT WORKS TO ADVANCE FUNDAMENTAL FAIRNESS IN U.S. IMMIGRATION LAW AND TO PROTECT THE CONSTITUTIONAL AND LEGAL RIGHTS OF NONCITIZENS. IN PURSUIT OF ITS MISSION, THE LEGAL DEPARTMENT HAS ESTABLISHED ITSELF AS A LEADER IN LITIGATION, INFORMATION-SHARING, AND COLLABORATION AMONG IMMIGRATION LITIGATORS ACROSS THE COUNTRY. THE LEGAL DEPARTMENT WORKS WITH OTHER IMMIGRANTS' RIGHTS, CIVIL RIGHTS AND HUMAN RIGHTS ORGANIZATIONS AND IMMIGRATION ATTORNEYS THROUGHOUT THE UNITED STATES TO PROMOTE THE JUST AND FAIR ADMINISTRATION OF OUR IMMIGRATION LAWS AND THE ACCOUNTABILITY OF IMMIGRATION AGENCIES.
column88: POLICY DEPARTMENT: THE COUNCIL'S POLICY DEPARTMENT IS THE POLICY AND RESEARCH ARM OF THE COUNCIL. IT IS DEDICATED TO PRODUCING AND SUPPORTING RESEARCH AND ANALYSIS ABOUT THE CONTRIBUTIONS MADE TO AMERICA BY IMMIGRANTS AND IMMIGRATION, PARTICULARLY FOCUSING ON THE ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL CONTRIBUTIONS MADE POSSIBLE BY A WELL REGULATED IMMIGRATION POLICY. THE POLICY DEPARTMENT PUBLISHES FACT SHEETS, PERSPECTIVES PIECES AND SPECIAL REPORTS. THE POLICY DEPARTMENT ALSO WORKS TO DISSEMINATE ITS STUDIES AND PAPERS TO A BROAD AUDIENCE OF BOTH NATIONAL POLICYMAKERS AND MEDIA AND LOCAL OPINION LEADERS IN CITIES THROUGHOUT THE COUNTRY. CONGRESSIONAL BRIEFINGS, PRESS CONFERENCES, AND SYMPOSIA ARE ALSO USED TO PRESENT OUR FINDINGS TO THE PUBLIC
column96: CULTURAL EXCHNGE PROGRAM (CEP): THE CULTURAL EXCHANGE PROGRAM(CEP) PROMOTES THE UNDERSTANDING OF TEMPORARY IMMIGRATION AND PARTICIPATION IN THE GLOBAL ECONOMY BY SPONSORING J-1 VISAS FOR INTERNATIONAL TRAINEES AND INTERNS AT U.S. BUSINESSES OF ALL SIZES. DESIGNATED BY THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF STATE TO OFFER AN EXCHANGE VISITOR PROGRAM, THE CEP FACILITATES EMERGING PROFESSIONALS TO DEVELOP CAREER ENHANCING SKILLS AT U.S. COMPANIES TO USE IN THEIR HOME COUNTRIES. THE PARTICIPATING BUSINESSES AND INSTITUTIONS WILL, IN TURN, BENEFIT FROM EXPOSURE TO VARYING CULTURES IN THE COUNTRIES INTO WHICH THEY ARE OPERATING OR INTO WHICH THEY ARE EXPANDING. SHORT TERM OUTBOUND PROGRAMS PERIODICALLY OFFER AMERICANS INTERESTED IN LEARNING ABOUT INTERNATIONAL IMMIGRATION AND HUMAN RIGHTS ISSUES, THE OPPORTUNITY TO PARTICIPATE IN OVERSEAS STUDY TOURS TO GAIN NEW PERSPECTIVES ON THESE VITAL ISSUES.

column40: THE CENTER FOR ECONOMIC AND POLICY RESEARCH (CEPR) IS COMMITTED TO PRESENTING ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL ISSUES IN AN ACCURATE, UNDERSTANDABLE MANNER TO THE PUBLIC SO THAT CITIZENS CAN BE INFORMED ABOUT PROBLEMS AND CHOICES THEY FACE TO EFFECTIVELY EXERCISE THEIR VOICES IN A DEMOCRACY.
column80: TO PROMOTE DEMOCRATIC DEBATE ON ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL ISSUES THROUGH PROFESSIONAL RESEARCH AND PUBLIC EDUCATION.
column84: DOMESTIC ECONOMIC POLICYCEPR ANALYZES GOVERNMENT DATA SETS ON THE NON-WAGE ASPECTS OF WORK AND DISSEMINATES THE FINDINGS WIDELY.
column88: GLOBALIZATIONCEPR PROVIDES RESEARCH AND EDUCATION ON WORLDWIDE ECONOMIC ISSUES AFFECTING GROWTH, DEVELOPMENT AND POVERTY.
