column40: THE INSTITUTE WAS FOUNDED WITH THE PRIMARY GOAL OF IDENTIFYING AND SOLVING IMPORTANT MATHEMATICAL PROBLEMS.
column80: THE INSTITUTE WAS FOUNDED WITH THE PRIMARY GOAL OF IDENTIFYING AND SOLVING IMPORTANT MATHEMATICAL PROBLEMS.
column84: AIM RESEARCH CONFERENCE CENTER (ARCC): A MODEL FOR COLLABORATIVE RESEARCHARCC HOSTS FOCUSED WORKSHOPS IN ALL AREAS OF THE MATHEMATICAL SCIENCES. ARCC FOCUSED WORKSHOPS ARE DISTINGUISHED BY THEIR EMPHASIS ON A SPECIFIC MATHEMATICAL GOAL, SUCH AS MAKING PROGRESS ON A SIGNIFICANT UNSOLVED PROBLEM, UNDERSTANDING THE PROOF OF AN IMPORTANT NEW RESULT, OR EXAMINING THE CONVERGENCE OF TWO DISTINCT AREAS OF MATHEMATICS.AIM FOCUSED WORKSHOPS PROVIDE AN IDEAL FORUM FOR A TEAM OF RESEARCHERS WORKING TOGETHER TO MAP OUT STRATEGIES, SET PRIORITIES, WORK TOWARD A SOLUTION, AND SET IN PLACE A FRAMEWORK FOR PROGRESS ON IMPORTANT MATHEMATICAL PROBLEMS. THE LEADERS IN EACH FIELD ARE INVOLVED IN THE PLANNING OF THE WORKSHOPS, AND JUNIOR SCIENTISTS AND GRADUATE STUDENTS ARE ACTIVE PARTICIPANTS. SPECIAL ATTENTION IS DEVOTED TO FACILITATE COLLABORATIONS WHICH INCLUDE WOMEN, MINORITIES, AND RESEARCHERS AT PRIMARILY UNDERGRADUATE INSTITUTIONS.THE PURPOSE OF AIM'S RESEARCH PROGRAM CALLED SQUARES (STRUCTURED QUARTET RESEARCH ENSEMBLES) IS TO ALLOW A DEDICATED GROUP OF FOUR TO SIX MATHEMATICIANS TO SPEND A WEEK AT AIM IN SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA WITH THE POSSIBILITY OF RETURNING IN FOLLOWING YEARS. A SQUARE COULD ARISE AS A FOLLOW-UP TO AN AIM WORKSHOP OR IT COULD BE A FREE-STANDING ACTIVITY. AIM WILL PROVIDE BOTH THE RESEARCH FACILITIES AND THE FINANCIAL SUPPORT FOR EACH SQUARE GROUP. AIM WILL SOLICIT SQUARE PROPOSALS IN ALL AREAS OF PURE AND APPLIED MATHEMATICS. PREFERENCE IS GIVEN TO GROUPS WHICH CONTAIN A MIX OF JUNIOR AND SENIOR RESEARCHERS AND TO GROUPS WHICH HAVE PARTICIPANTS FROM NORTH AMERICA. SQUARES USUALLY MEET DURING WEEKS WHEN THERE ARE NO ARCC WORKSHOPS SCHEDULED.EIGHTEEN WORKSHOPS WERE HELD IN 2015 INVOLVING 485 PARTICIPANTS.FORTY-EIGHT SQUARES WORKSHOPS WERE HELD IN 2015 INVOLVING 222 PARTICIPANTS.
column88: DIRECTED GRANTS:THE FOLLOWING DIRECTED GRANTS WERE ACTIVE DURING 2015:1. MONGE-AMPERE EQUATIONS AND MICROLOCAL ANALYSIS ON KAHLER MANIFOLDSTHIS PROJECT FOCUSES ON PROBLEMS MAINLY IN DIFFERENTIAL GEOMETRY AND GEOMETRIC ANALYSIS THAT CAN BE FORMULATED AS REAL AND COMPLEX MONGE-AMPERE TYPE EQUATIONS. PROGRESS CONTINUED THROUGH 2015 BY THE PI.2. RESEARCH EXPERIENCES FOR UNDERGRADUATE FACULTY (REUF)THE GOALS OF REUF ARE (A) TO REKINDLE OR ENHANCE A LOVE OF DOING ORIGINAL MATHEMATICS AMONG UNDERGRADUATE FACULTY PARTICIPANTS, (B) TO PREPARE PARTICIPANTS TO ENGAGE IN RESEARCH WITH UNDERGRADUATE STUDENTS AT THEIR HOME INSTITUTIONS, IN SOME CASES USING THE PROBLEMS PRESENTED, (C) TO INCOLVE SOME PARTICIPANTS IN LONG-TERM RESEARCH COLLABORATIONS, AND (D)TO ESTABLISH A NETWORK OF FACULTY AT PRIMARILY UNDERGRADUATE INSTITUTIONS TOGETHER WITH FACULTY AT RESEARCH UNIVERSITIES WHO SUPPORT COLLABORATION AND UNDERGRADUATE RESEARCH. PROGRESS CONTINUED THROUGH 2015 BY THE PI.3. OPEN RESOURCES FOR THE MATHEMATICAL CURRICULUMTHIS EXPLORATION PROJECT WILL (1) PROVIDE MATERIALS SUCH AS TEXTBOOK CONTENT, VIDEOS, INTERACTIVE APPLETS, AND INSTRUCTOR GUIDES; (2) IDENTIFY OPTIMAL METHODS FOR BUILDING COMPREHENSIVE, QUALITY-CONTROLLED, AND CURATED LIBRARIES OF FREELY REUSABLE INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS FOR COLLEGE-LEVEL MATHEMATICS COURSES; AND (3) INVESTIGATE THE IMPACT OF SUCH A LIBRARY ON FACULTY ADOPTION OF EVIDENCE-BASED TEACHING PRACTICES. THE MATERIALS WILL BE CREATED AND CURATED COLLABORATIVELY, AND THE PROJECT WILL PROVIDE TRAINING IN THE DEVELOPMENT AND USE OF SUCH CONTENT. THE PROJECT WILL EXPLORE HOW THIS NEW APPROACH ENABLES INSTRUCTORS TO LOCATE AND UTILIZE A VARIETY OF CURRICULAR MATERIALS IN THE CLASSROOM. PROGRESS CONTINUED THROUGH 2015 BY THE PI.
column96: INVESTIGATING THE IMPACT OF MATH TEACHERS' CIRCLES ON MATHEMATICAL KNOWLEDGE FOR TEACHING AND CLASSROOM PRACTICE:THE MATH TEACHERS' CIRCLE PROJECT (MTC) IS CONNECTING MATHEMATICIANS AND MATHEMATICS TEACHERS IN MIDDLE SCHOOLS BY OFFERING SUMMER WORKSHOPS AND CONTINUED COMMUNICATION THROUGHOUT THE YEAR. THE WORKSHOPS FOCUS ON MATHEMATICAL PROBLEM SOLVING AND INCLUDE ACTIVITIES THAT OFFER MULTIPLE ENTRY POINTS. THE GOAL OF THE WORKSHOPS IS TO INCREASE TEACHERS' KNOWLEDGE OF MATHEMATICS FOR TEACHING AND TO HELP TEACHERS USE THEIR KNOWLEDGE TO IMPROVE STUDENT LEARNING OF MATHEMATICS. IN ADDITION TO CONDUCTING WORKSHOPS, RESEARCHERS ARE INVESTIGATING WHAT MATHEMATICAL TEACHERS LEARN BY PARTICIPATING IN THE WORKSHOPS AND HOW TEACHERS USE WHAT THEY HAVE LEARNED IN THEIR MATHEMATICAL TEACHING. PROGRESS CONTINUED THROUGH 2015 BY THE PI.

column40: THE CONCILIO BEGAN AS DALLAS CONCILIO OF HISPANIC SERVICE ORGANIZATIONS AND IN 2010 CHANGED ITS NAME TO THE CONCILIO. FOUNDED IN 1981 TO FILL THE ROLE OF COLLABORATIVE PARTNER IN RESPONSE TO THE NEEDS OF AN EMERGING HISPANIC POPULATION, THE CONCILIO EDUCATED NONPROFITS AND OTHER AGENCIES ON EFFECTIVELY REACHING THIS GROWING DEMOGRAPHIC. FOR 35 YEARS, THE CONCILIO HAS SPECIALIZED IN OUTREACH TO THE HISPANIC COMMUNITY, AS WELL AS ACTIVELY WORKING WITH OTHER EFFECTIVE, EXISTING LOCAL AGENCIES. TODAY THE CONCILIO PROVIDES DIRECT SERVICES THAT FULFILL ITS MISSION "TO BUILD STRONGER COMMUNITIES BY EMPOWERING PARENTS TO IMPROVE THE EDUCATION AND HEALTH OF THEIR FAMILIES."
column80: THE CONCILIO BEGAN AS DALLAS CONCILIO OF HISPANIC SERVICE ORGANIZATIONS AND IN 2010 CHANGED ITS NAME TO THE CONCILIO. FOUNDED IN 1981 TO FILL THE ROLE OF COLLABORATIVE PARTNER IN RESPONSE TO THE NEEDS OF AN EMERGING HISPANIC POPULATION, THE CONCILIO EDUCATED NONPROFITS AND OTHER AGENCIES ON EFFECTIVELY REACHING THIS GROWING DEMOGRAPHIC. FOR 35 YEARS, THE CONCILIO HAS SPECIALIZED IN OUTREACH TO THE HISPANIC COMMUNITY, AS WELL AS ACTIVELY WORKING WITH OTHER EFFECTIVE, EXISTING LOCAL AGENCIES. TODAY THE CONCILIO PROVIDES DIRECT SERVICES THAT FULFILL ITS MISSION "TO BUILD STRONGER COMMUNITIES BY EMPOWERING PARENTS TO IMPROVE THE EDUCATION AND HEALTH OF THEIR FAMILIES."
column84: THE CONCILIO'S PARENTS ADVOCATING FOR STUDENT EXCELLENCE (PASE) TEACHES PARENTS HOW TO POSITIVELY IMPACT THEIR CHILD'S EDUCATION BY BEING ACTIVELY ENGAGED - THEY ARE TAUGHT HOW TO NAVIGATE THE SCHOOL SYSTEM, IDENTIFY ACADEMIC CHALLENGES, AND HOW TO PROVIDE A SUPPORTIVE HOME-LEARNING ENVIRONMENT. DURING 2015 THE CONCILIO SERVED 7,676 INDIVIDUALS THROUGH THIS PROGRAM.
column88: THE CONCILIO'S COMMUNITY HEALTH DEPARTMENT INCLUDES A HOLISTIC FAMILY NUTRITION AND WELLNESS PROGRAM WITH THE LONG-TERM GOAL OF GENERATING LASTING POSITIVE HEALTH BEHAVIORS IN THE LIVES OF PARENTS AND THEIR CHILDREN TO REDUCE RISK FACTORS FOR NUTRITION-RELATED CHRONIC DISEASE AND TO POSTPONE THE ONSET OF DISEASE BY ENCOURAGING PARTICIPANTS TO ESTABLISH HEALTHY HABITS EARLY ON. TO MEET THIS GOAL, WE TEACH PARENTS HOW TO HELP THEIR CHILDREN BE MORE ACTIVE AND DEVELOP HEALTHY HABITS FOR LIFE. MOREOVER, CHILDREN LEARN AT AN EARLY AGE HOW TO MAKE GOOD DECISIONS FOR THEIR OWN HEALTH. WE ALSO PROVIDE OUR FAMILIES WITH LINKAGE TO HEALTHCARE: PARTICIPANTS RECEIVE ONE-ON-ONE ASSISTANCE WITH ENROLLING INTO CHILDREN'S HEALTH INSURANCE (CHIP), MEDICAID AND SNAP (SUPPLEMENTAL NUTRITION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM). ADDITIONALLY, WE CAN ASSIST THEM WITH NAVIGATING THE HEALTH INSURANCE MARKETPLACE AND ENROLLING INTO QUALIFIED HEALTH PLANS. DURING 2015 THE CONCILIO SERVED 4,447 INDIVIDUALS THROUGH THIS PROGRAM.
column96: THE CONCILIO'S COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT DEPARTMENT OVERSEES A COMMUNITY ACTION NETWORK (CAN). CAN WAS DEVELOPED TO HELP BUILD A WHOLE COMMUNITY WHERE FAMILIES TAKE OWNERSHIP AS THE LEADERS AND DECISION MAKERS. CAN HAS ESTABLISHED A UNIQUE MODEL IN WHICH THE PARENT LEADERS OF THE PROGRAM, ALL LOW-INCOME MOTHERS, ARE SEATED AT THE DECISION-MAKING TABLE AND HAVE BEEN FULLY INTEGRATED INTO ALL LEVELS OF DEVELOPMENT, PLANNING, AND IMPLEMENTATION OF EACH PROJECT AND ACTIVITY. EQUIPPING AND SUPPORTING MOTHERS TO BE LEADERS IN THEIR NEIGHBORHOODS, TO BE CIVICALLY ENGAGED AND TO BUILD A SENSE OF COMMUNITY IS THE BEST WAY TO CREATE WHOLE COMMUNITIES THAT COLLECTIVELY SUPPORT SCHOOL READINESS FOR THE LONG TERM. DURING 2015, THE CONCILIO SERVED 56 INDIVIDUALS THROUGH THIS PROGRAM.

column40: PRESERVES AND REVITALIZES OUR INLAND NORTHWEST FORESTS, WATER, AND WILDLIFE THROUGH ADVOCACY, EDUCATION, EFFECTIVE ACTION, AND COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT.
column80: PRESERVES AND REVITALIZES OUR INLAND NORTHWEST FORESTS, WATER, AND WILDLIFE THROUGH ADVOCACY, EDUCATION, EFFECTIVE ACTION, AND COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT.
column84: NATIONAL AND URBAN FOREST DEFENSE PROGRAM: TLC'S FOREST WATCH TEAM MONITORS TIMBER SALES AND FOREST CONDITIONS TO ENSURE OUR PUBLIC LANDS ARE MANAGED IN A LEGAL, SUSTAINABLE MANNER UNDER THE ENVIRONMENTAL LAWS, INCLUDING THE NATIONAL ENVIROMENTAL POLICY ACT, CLEAN WATER ACT, NATIONAL FOREST PLANS AND ENDANGERED SPECIES ACT. THE LANDS COUNCIL EDUCATES THE PUBLIC ABOUT FOREST ECOLOGY AND HOW TO BECOME INVOLVED IN DECISION-MAKING ABOUT OUR PUBLIC FOREST LANDS. TLC ADVOCATES FOR FOREST ECOSYSTEMS BY USING SCIENCE, COLLABORATION, AND CITIZEN PARTICIPATION TO WORK TOWARDS ECOLOGICALLY SUSTAINABLE MANAGEMENT OF OUR INLAND NORTHWEST NATIONAL FORESTS. THIS PROGRAM ALSO INCLUDES THE URBAN RESTORATION AND PRESERVATION OF OUR NATIVE PONDEROSA PINE TREE POPULATION.
column88: WATERSHED PROTECTION & RESTORATION PROGRAM: PROTECT THE HEADWATERS OF THE IDAHO PANHANDLE NATIONAL FOREST SO THE SPOKANE AQUIFER CAN CONTINUE TO PROVIDE PURE WATER FOR REGIONAL RESIDENTS. WORK WITH MUNICIPALITIES ON WATER CONSERVATION, WATER STORAGE, WASTEWATER TREATMENT, AND PROTECTION OF THE SPOKANE RIVER. BEAVER PROJECT: IDENTIFY PHYSICAL LOCATIONS FOR BEAVER DAMS BASED ON THE BEST SUITABLE HABITAT FOR BEAVERS, AND PROVIDE ESTIMATES OF WATER STORAGE POTENTIAL AND ADDRESS THE SOCIAL AND ECONOMIC BENEFITS, INCLUDING OPPORTUNITIES FOR WATER BANKING AND CONSERVATION EASEMENTS. WORK WITH PROPERTY OWNERS WITH NUISANCE BEAVERS AND RELOCATE FAMILIES TO NATURAL AREAS.
column96: URBAN ECOLOGY PROGRAM: EDUCATE CITIZENS OF THE TOXIC LEGACY RESULTING FROM A CENTURY OF MINING IN THE SPOKANE AND COEUR D'ALENE WATERSHED. DISTRIBUTE MATERIALS ABOUT THE RISKS FROM EXPOSURE TO TOXICS IN THE SPOKANE RIVER. WORK WITH LOW-INCOME AND MINORITY COMMUNITIES AND EDUCATE THEM ABOUT TOXICS IN THE RIVER AND LEAD EXPOSURE RISKS IN OUR COMMUNITY NEIGHBORHOODS. THIS PROGRAM ALSO INCLUDES IMPLEMENTING URBAN EFFORTS, THROUGH LOCAL PARTNERSHIPS, TO DECREASE AIR POLLUTION, SAFEGUARD AIR QUALITY, BUILD COMMUNITY AND ENHANCE OVERALL QUALITY OF LIFE IN SPOKANE. THROUGH PROJECT SUSTAIN, WE WORK WITH LOCAL SCHOOLS TO GET STUDENTS OUTSIDE AND ENGAGE IN HANDS-ON, SCIENCE-BASED LEARNING ACTIVITIES AND COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECTS.

column80: Voluntary, cooperative, non-profit savings institution (credit union) incorporated under the provisions of the Texas Credit Union Act, for the purpose of encouraging thrift among our members, providing credit at a fair and reasonable rate of interest and providing an opportunity to improve our member's economic condition.
column84: Gulf Credit Union offers share (savings) accounts with advantages to members of all ages. The credit union had 27,179 member-owned accounts as of December 31, 2015. Member savings accounts pay dividends quarterly and offer access via multiple avenues such as home banking, the Internet, and phone banking.
column88: Gulf Credit Union provides free share draft (checking) accounts to all members, business accounts, and limited free checks to senior citizens. The credit union had 14,213 share draft accounts as of December 31, 2015. Dividends are paid on these accounts monthly. Additionally, the credit union extends the reach of these accounts to all members with free debit and ATM cards, Internet account access, and the use of the automated phone teller.
column96: Gulf Credit Union provides vehicle and other consumer loans. The consumer loan product line includes efficient underwriting and flexible offerings for recreational vehicles, boats, and motorcycles. Consumer credit life and disability insurance is available on any of these loan types. The credit union carried 3,474 consumer loans as of December 31, 2015.

column80: THE MISSION OF HOLDEN VILLAGE, A LUTHERAN MINISTRY, IS TO WELCOME ALL PEOPLE INTO THE WILDERNESS TO BE CALLED, EQUIPPED AND SENT BY GOD AS WE SHARE RHYTHMS OF WORD AND SACRAMENT, WORK, RECREATION AND STUDY, INTERCESSION AND HEALING.
column84: WELCOMING ALL PEOPLE INTO THE WILDERNESS TO BE CALLED, EQUIPPED AND SENT BY GOD AS WE SHARE THE RHYTHMS OF WORD AND SACRAMENT, RECREATION AND STUDY, INTERCESSION AND HEALING. FOR THE FY ENDING 10-31-15 HOLDEN VILLAGE SERVED OVER 3,700 GUESTS. HOLDEN ALSO RECEIVES SUPPORT IN THE FORM OF VOLUNTEER LABOR. FOR THE FY ENDING 10-31-15: 1) 9 VOLUNTEERS PROVIDED SPECIALIZED LABOR WORTH $161,302 TO REMODEL BUILDINGS AND MAINTAIN AGING UTILITY SYSTEMS AND PROVIDE NOURISHING MEALS, 2) SKILLED LABOR (TEACHING STAFF, MEDICS, BOOKKEEPERS, CARPENTERS, ETC.) WORTH $14,505 WHEN COMPUTED AT $26.05/HOUR, 3) COMMON OR "UNSKILLED" LABOR INTEGRAL TO OPERATIONS WORTH $126,172 WHEN COMPUTED AT MINIMUM WAGE. THIS TOTALED 6,192 HOURS OF SKILLED AND 34,785 HOURS OF COMMON LABOR.
column88: HOLDEN VILLAGE OPERATES A BOOKSTORE WHICH PROVIDES BOOKS, RECORDED AND WRITTEN MUSIC, CARDS, CLOTHING ITEMS, CRAFTS, POTTERY, JEWELRY, AND OTHER RESOURCES TO GUESTS, STAFF, AND MINE REMEDIATION WORKERS. RESOURCE MATERIALS ARE IN KEEPING WITH THE HOLDEN MISSION OF HEALING, INTERCESSION, ENVIRONMENTAL STEWARDSHIP, SACRAMENT, AND GOOD HUMOR. IN ADDITION, THE BOOKSTORE SUPPLIES A SMALL AMOUNT OF MERCANTILE GOODS FOR SALE TO GUESTS, STAFF, AND MINE REMEDIATION WORKERS, SUCH AS TOOTHBRUSHES, TOOTHPASTE, CAMPING SUPPLIES, PENS AND PAPER, SNACK ITEMS, ETC.
column96: IN ADDITION, HOLDEN HAS A VARIETY OF OTHER PROGRAMS THAT OPERATE WITHIN THE OVERALL FUNCTIONING OF THE MISSION AND PURPOSE OF THE VILLAGE, INCLUDING ARTS & CRAFTS, POTTERY, POOL HALL/BOWLING ALLEY, SNACK BAR, ESPRESSO STAND, BOARDING STUDENTS, SPONSORING JAPANESE FOREIGN STUDENTS, AND OTHER MISCELLANEOUS PROGRAM ACTIVITY.
